fitk.fisher_plotter

Submodule for plotting of Fisher objects. See here for documentation of FisherFigure1D and FisherFigure2D.

   1"""
   2Submodule for plotting of Fisher objects.
   3See here for documentation of `FisherFigure1D` and `FisherFigure2D`.
   4"""
   5
   6# needed for compatibility with Python 3.7
   7from __future__ import annotations
   8
   9# standard library imports
  10import copy
  11import os
  12from abc import ABC, abstractmethod
  13from collections.abc import MutableSequence
  14from itertools import product
  15from pathlib import Path
  16from typing import Any, Optional, Union
  17
  18# third party imports
  19import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
  20import numpy as np
  21from matplotlib.artist import Artist
  22from matplotlib.axes import Axes
  23from matplotlib.figure import Figure
  24from matplotlib.patches import Ellipse
  25from matplotlib.ticker import Formatter, Locator
  26from matplotlib.transforms import Bbox
  27from scipy.stats import chi2, norm
  28
  29# first party imports
  30from fitk.fisher_matrix import FisherMatrix
  31from fitk.fisher_utils import ParameterNotFoundError, get_default_rcparams, is_iterable
  32
  33
  34class EmptyFigureError(Exception):
  35    """
  36    Error raised when the figure is empty, i.e. `plot` was not called first.
  37    """
  38
  39    def __init__(self):
  40        self.message = "No parameters on the figure; did you forget to call `plot`?"
  41        super().__init__(self.message)
  42
  43
  44class FisherBaseFigure(ABC):
  45    """
  46    The abstract base class for plotting Fisher objects.
  47    """
  48
  49    def __init__(
  50        self,
  51        *args,
  52        options: Optional[dict] = None,
  53        hspace: float = 0.1,
  54        wspace: float = 0.1,
  55        **kwargs,
  56    ):
  57        """
  58        Constructor
  59        """
  60        self._figure = None
  61        self._axes = None
  62        self._handles: MutableSequence[Artist] = []
  63        self._names = None
  64        self._labels: MutableSequence[str] = []
  65        self._options: dict = get_default_rcparams()
  66        self._ndim: int = 0
  67        self._hspace = hspace
  68        self._wspace = wspace
  69
  70        self.cycler = plt.rcParams["axes.prop_cycle"].by_key()["color"]
  71        self.current_color = iter(self.cycler)
  72
  73        if options and "style" in options:
  74            style = options.pop("style")
  75            # maybe it's one of the built-in styles
  76            if style in plt.style.available:
  77                self._options = {
  78                    **plt.style.library[style],
  79                    **get_default_rcparams(),
  80                    **options,
  81                }
  82                # we need to reset the color cycler
  83                self.cycler = (
  84                    plt.style.library[style]
  85                    .get(
  86                        "axes.prop_cycle",
  87                        plt.rcParams["axes.prop_cycle"],
  88                    )
  89                    .by_key()["color"]
  90                )
  91                self.current_color = iter(self.cycler)
  92
  93            # maybe it's a file
  94            else:
  95                # we need to reset the color cycler
  96                self.cycler = (
  97                    plt.style.core.rc_params_from_file(style)
  98                    .get(
  99                        "axes.prop_cycle",
 100                        plt.rcParams["axes.prop_cycle"],
 101                    )
 102                    .by_key()["color"]
 103                )
 104                self.current_color = iter(self.cycler)
 105
 106                self._options = {
 107                    **plt.style.core.rc_params_from_file(style),
 108                    **options,
 109                }
 110
 111    @abstractmethod
 112    def plot(self, fisher: FisherMatrix, *args, **kwargs):
 113        """
 114        Implements plotting of Fisher objects.
 115        """
 116        return NotImplemented
 117
 118    @abstractmethod
 119    def __getitem__(self, key):
 120        """
 121        Implements element access.
 122        """
 123        return NotImplemented
 124
 125    @property
 126    def figure(self):
 127        """
 128        Returns the underlying figure, an instance of
 129        `matplotlib.figure.Figure`.
 130        """
 131        return self._figure
 132
 133    @property
 134    def axes(self):
 135        """
 136        Returns the axes of the figure as a numpy array.
 137        """
 138        return self._axes
 139
 140    @property
 141    def hspace(self) -> float:
 142        """
 143        The amount of height reserved for space between subplots, expressed as
 144        a fraction of the average axis height.
 145        """
 146        return self._hspace
 147
 148    @property
 149    def wspace(self) -> float:
 150        """
 151        The amount of width reserved for space between subplots, expressed as a
 152        fraction of the average axis width.
 153        """
 154        return self._wspace
 155
 156    @property
 157    def names(self):
 158        """
 159        Returns the names of the original parameters plotted.
 160        """
 161        return self._names
 162
 163    @property
 164    def handles(self):
 165        """
 166        Returns the handles of the currently drawn artists.
 167        """
 168        return self._handles
 169
 170    @property
 171    def labels(self):
 172        """
 173        Returns the legend labels of the currently drawn artists.
 174        """
 175        return self._labels
 176
 177    @property
 178    def options(self):
 179        """
 180        Returns the matplotlib options which were used for plotting.
 181        """
 182        return self._options
 183
 184    def __repr__(self):
 185        """
 186        Returns the representation of the figure
 187        """
 188        return (
 189            f"<FisherFigure(\n"
 190            f"    names={repr(self.names)},\n"
 191            f"    figure={repr(self.figure)},\n"
 192            f"    axes={repr(self.axes)})>"
 193        )
 194
 195    def __str__(self):
 196        """
 197        Returns the string representation of the figure
 198        """
 199        return (
 200            f"FisherFigure(\n"
 201            f"    names={str(self.names)},\n"
 202            f"    figure={str(self.figure)},\n"
 203            f"    axes={str(self.axes)})"
 204        )
 205
 206    def add_artist_to_legend(
 207        self,
 208        artist: Artist,
 209        label: str,
 210    ):
 211        r"""
 212        This is a convenience function for correctly updating the legend after
 213        directly plotting some artist via `<instance>[<name(s)>].<method>`
 214
 215        Parameters
 216        ----------
 217        artist
 218            the artist which we want to put on the legend
 219
 220        label : str
 221            the label for the artist
 222
 223        Returns
 224        -------
 225        None
 226
 227        Examples
 228        --------
 229        Setup the plot:
 230        >>> fig = FisherFigure1D()
 231        >>> fig.plot(FisherMatrix(np.diag([1, 2]), names=["a", "b"]), label="Fisher matrix")
 232
 233        Add something to the plot that has a handle:
 234        >>> handle, = fig["a"].plot([-1, 0, 1], [-1, 0, 1], color='red')
 235
 236        Finally, add the handle to the legend, and draw the legend:
 237        >>> fig.add_artist_to_legend(handle, "linear function")
 238        >>> _ = fig.legend() # the artist will now be shown correctly in the legend
 239
 240        Save it to a file:
 241        >>> fig.savefig(
 242        ... Path(__file__).parent.parent / os.environ.get("TEMP_IMAGE_DIR") / "fisher_figure2d_add_artist_to_legend1.png",
 243        ... dpi=150)
 244

 246
 247        Notes
 248        -----
 249        The limits of the plot are not updated automatically.
 250        """
 251        self.labels.append(label)
 252        self.handles.append(artist)
 253
 254    def savefig(
 255        self,
 256        path: Path,
 257        dpi: float = 300,
 258        bbox_inches: Union[str, Bbox] = "tight",
 259        **kwargs,
 260    ):
 261        """
 262        Convenience wrapper for `figure.savefig`.
 263
 264        Parameters
 265        ----------
 266        path : Path
 267            the path where to save the figure
 268
 269        dpi : float, optional
 270            the resolution of the saved figure (default: 300)
 271
 272        bbox_inches : str or Bbox, optional
 273            what is the bounding box for the figure (default: 'tight')
 274
 275        **kwargs
 276            any other keyword arguments that should be passed to
 277            `figure.savefig`
 278
 279        Returns
 280        -------
 281        None
 282
 283        Raises
 284        ------
 285        EmptyFigureError
 286            if `plot` hasn't been called yet
 287        """
 288        if not self.figure:
 289            raise EmptyFigureError
 290
 291        self.figure.savefig(
 292            path,
 293            dpi=dpi,
 294            bbox_inches=bbox_inches,
 295            **kwargs,
 296        )
 297
 298    def set_label_params(
 299        self,
 300        which: str = "both",
 301        **kwargs,
 302    ):
 303        """
 304        Collectively sets both x and y label parameters.
 305
 306        Parameters
 307        ----------
 308        which : {'both', 'x', 'y'}
 309            which axis to change (default: 'both')
 310
 311        **kwargs
 312            any keyword arguments that are also valid for
 313            `matplotlib.text.Text`, see [the
 314            documentation](https://matplotlib.org/stable/api/text_api.html#matplotlib.text.Text)
 315            for details
 316
 317        Returns
 318        -------
 319        None
 320
 321        Raises
 322        ------
 323        EmptyFigureError
 324            if `plot` hasn't been called yet
 325        """
 326        if not self.figure:
 327            raise EmptyFigureError
 328
 329        for nameiter in product(self.names, repeat=self._ndim):
 330            # only set the parameters which are not empty (should this be done
 331            # for all of them instead?)
 332            if (
 333                self[nameiter]
 334                and self[nameiter].get_xlabel()
 335                and which in ["both", "x"]
 336            ):
 337                self[nameiter].set_xlabel(
 338                    self[nameiter].get_xlabel(),
 339                    **kwargs,
 340                )
 341            if (
 342                self[nameiter]
 343                and self[nameiter].get_ylabel()
 344                and which in ["both", "y"]
 345            ):
 346                self[nameiter].set_ylabel(
 347                    self[nameiter].get_ylabel(),
 348                    **kwargs,
 349                )
 350
 351    def set_tick_params(
 352        self,
 353        which: str = "both",
 354        **kwargs,
 355    ):
 356        """
 357        Collectively sets both x and y tick parameters.
 358
 359        Parameters
 360        ----------
 361        which : {'both', 'x', 'y'}
 362            which axis to change (default: 'both')
 363
 364        **kwargs
 365            any keyword arguments passed to the methods for handling tick
 366            parameters (such as 'fontsize', 'rotation', etc.)
 367
 368        Returns
 369        -------
 370        None
 371
 372        Raises
 373        ------
 374        EmptyFigureError
 375            if `plot` hasn't been called yet
 376        """
 377        if not self.figure:
 378            raise EmptyFigureError
 379
 380        for nameiter in product(self.names, repeat=self._ndim):
 381            if self[nameiter] and which in ["both", "x"]:
 382                for item in self[nameiter].get_xticklabels():
 383                    for key, value in kwargs.items():
 384                        getattr(item, f"set_{key}")(value)
 385            if self[nameiter] and which in ["both", "y"]:
 386                for item in self[nameiter].get_yticklabels():
 387                    for key, value in kwargs.items():
 388                        getattr(item, f"set_{key}")(value)
 389            # also alter any exponential offsets
 390            for key, value in kwargs.items():
 391                if self[nameiter] and which in ["both", "x"]:
 392                    getattr(
 393                        self[nameiter].get_xaxis().get_offset_text(),
 394                        f"set_{key}",
 395                    )(value)
 396                if self[nameiter] and which in ["both", "y"]:
 397                    getattr(
 398                        self[nameiter].get_yaxis().get_offset_text(),
 399                        f"set_{key}",
 400                    )(value)
 401
 402    def set_major_locator(
 403        self,
 404        locator: Locator,
 405        which: str = "both",
 406    ):
 407        """
 408        Sets the major locator for all of the axes.
 409
 410        Parameters
 411        ----------
 412        locator
 413            the instance of `matplotlib.ticker.Locator` to use.
 414
 415        which : {'both', 'x', 'y'}
 416            which axis to change (default: 'both')
 417
 418        Returns
 419        -------
 420        None
 421
 422        Raises
 423        ------
 424        EmptyFigureError
 425            if `plot` hasn't been called yet
 426        """
 427        if not self.figure:
 428            raise EmptyFigureError
 429
 430        for nameiter in product(self.names, repeat=self._ndim):
 431            # for some reason, we cannot reuse the same instance, so we just
 432            # make a deep copy of it instead
 433            if (
 434                self[nameiter]
 435                and np.any(self[nameiter].get_xticks())
 436                and which in ["both", "x"]
 437            ):
 438                xloc = copy.deepcopy(locator)
 439                self[nameiter].xaxis.set_major_locator(xloc)
 440            if (
 441                self[nameiter]
 442                and np.any(self[nameiter].get_yticks())
 443                and which in ["both", "y"]
 444            ):
 445                yloc = copy.deepcopy(locator)
 446                self[nameiter].yaxis.set_major_locator(yloc)
 447
 448    def set_minor_locator(
 449        self,
 450        locator: Locator,
 451        which: str = "both",
 452    ):
 453        """
 454        Sets the minor locator for all of the axes.
 455
 456        Parameters
 457        ----------
 458        locator
 459            the instance of `matplotlib.ticker.Locator` to use.
 460
 461        which : {'both', 'x', 'y'}
 462            which axis to change (default: 'both')
 463
 464        Returns
 465        -------
 466        None
 467
 468        Raises
 469        ------
 470        EmptyFigureError
 471            if `plot` hasn't been called yet
 472        """
 473        if not self.figure:
 474            raise EmptyFigureError
 475
 476        for nameiter in product(self.names, repeat=self._ndim):
 477            if (
 478                self[nameiter]
 479                and np.any(self[nameiter].get_xticks())
 480                and which in ["both", "x"]
 481            ):
 482                # same reason as the major locator
 483                xloc = copy.deepcopy(locator)
 484                self[nameiter].xaxis.set_minor_locator(xloc)
 485            if (
 486                self[nameiter]
 487                and np.any(self[nameiter].get_yticks())
 488                and which in ["both", "y"]
 489            ):
 490                yloc = copy.deepcopy(locator)
 491                self[nameiter].yaxis.set_minor_locator(yloc)
 492
 493    def set_major_formatter(
 494        self,
 495        formatter: Formatter,
 496        which: str = "both",
 497    ):
 498        """
 499        Sets the major formatter for all of the axes.
 500
 501        Parameters
 502        ----------
 503        formatter
 504            the instance of `matplotlib.ticker.Formatter` to use.
 505
 506        which : {'both', 'x', 'y'}
 507            which axis to change (default: 'both')
 508
 509        Returns
 510        -------
 511        None
 512
 513        Raises
 514        ------
 515        EmptyFigureError
 516            if `plot` hasn't been called yet
 517        """
 518        if not self.figure:
 519            raise EmptyFigureError
 520
 521        for nameiter in product(self.names, repeat=self._ndim):
 522            if self[nameiter] and which in ["both", "x"]:
 523                self[nameiter].xaxis.set_major_formatter(formatter)
 524            if self[nameiter] and which in ["both", "y"]:
 525                self[nameiter].yaxis.set_major_formatter(formatter)
 526
 527    def set_minor_formatter(
 528        self,
 529        formatter: Formatter,
 530        which: str = "both",
 531    ):
 532        """
 533        Sets the minor formatter for all of the axes.
 534
 535        Parameters
 536        ----------
 537        formatter
 538            the instance of `matplotlib.ticker.Formatter` to use.
 539
 540        which : {'both', 'x', 'y'}
 541            which axis to change (default: 'both')
 542
 543        Returns
 544        -------
 545        None
 546
 547        Raises
 548        ------
 549        EmptyFigureError
 550            if `plot` hasn't been called yet
 551        """
 552        if not self.figure:
 553            raise EmptyFigureError
 554
 555        for nameiter in product(self.names, repeat=self._ndim):
 556            if self[nameiter] and which in ["both", "x"]:
 557                self[nameiter].xaxis.set_minor_formatter(formatter)
 558            if self[nameiter] and which in ["both", "y"]:
 559                self[nameiter].yaxis.set_minor_formatter(formatter)

 561
 562class FisherFigure1D(FisherBaseFigure):
 563    r"""
 564    Container for easy access to elements in the 1D plot.
 565
 566    Examples
 567    --------
 568    Define some Fisher matrices:
 569    >>> m1 = FisherMatrix(
 570    ... [[3, -2], [-2, 5]],
 571    ... names=['a', 'b'],
 572    ... latex_names=[r'$\mathcal{A}$', r'$\mathcal{B}$'],
 573    ... )
 574    >>> m2 = FisherMatrix(
 575    ... [[4, 1], [1, 6]],
 576    ... names=['a', 'b'],
 577    ... latex_names=[r'$\mathcal{A}$', r'$\mathcal{B}$'],
 578    ... )
 579
 580    Instantiate a figure:
 581    >>> fig = FisherFigure1D()
 582
 583    Draw marginalized 1D plots with the previously defined Fisher matrix:
 584    >>> fig.plot(m1, label='first')
 585
 586    Add another plot with a different color and style:
 587    >>> fig.plot(m2, label='second', ls=':', color='green')
 588
 589    Draw some other stuff on it:
 590    >>> artist, = fig.draw('a', 'plot', [-1, 0, 1], [-1, 0, 1], color='red')
 591    >>> # alternatively, the below will accomplish the same thing
 592    >>> # artist, = fig['a'].plot([-1, 0, 1], [-1, 0, 1], color='red')
 593
 594    Caveat for the above: make sure to update the legend with this artist:
 595    >>> fig.add_artist_to_legend(artist, label='curve')
 596
 597    Add a legend:
 598    >>> _ = fig.legend(ncol=3, loc='center')
 599
 600    Add a title:
 601    >>> _ = fig.set_title('Example Fisher matrix 1D plotting')
 602
 603    Save it to a file:
 604    >>> fig.savefig(
 605    ... Path(__file__).parent.parent / os.environ.get("TEMP_IMAGE_DIR") / "fisher_figure1d_example1.png",
 606    ... dpi=150)

 609    """
 610
 611    def __init__(
 612        self,
 613        options: Optional[dict] = None,
 614        max_cols: Optional[int] = None,
 615        hspace: float = 0.5,
 616        wspace: float = 0.1,
 617    ):
 618        """
 619        Constructor.
 620
 621        Parameters
 622        ----------
 623        options : dict, optional
 624            the dictionary containing the options for plotting. If the special
 625            key 'style' is present, it attempts to use that plotting style (can
 626            be one of the outputs of `matplotlib.pyplot.style.available`, or a
 627            path to a file. If using a file, does not use the default rc
 628            parameters).
 629
 630        max_cols : int, optional
 631            the maximum number of columns in the final plot
 632
 633        hspace : float, optional
 634            The amount of height reserved for space between subplots, expressed
 635            as a fraction of the average axis height.
 636
 637        wspace : float, optional
 638            The amount of width reserved for space between subplots, expressed
 639            as a fraction of the average axis width.
 640
 641        Notes
 642        -----
 643        For the style sheet reference, please consult [the matplotlib
 644        documentation](https://matplotlib.org/stable/gallery/style_sheets/style_sheets_reference.html).
 645        """
 646        super().__init__(options=options, wspace=wspace, hspace=hspace)
 647        self.max_cols = max_cols
 648        self._ndim = 1
 649        self._hspace = hspace
 650        self._wspace = wspace
 651
 652    def __getitem__(
 653        self,
 654        key: str,
 655    ):
 656        """
 657        Returns the axis associated to the name `key`.
 658        """
 659        if not self.figure:
 660            raise EmptyFigureError
 661
 662        if key not in self.names:
 663            raise ParameterNotFoundError(key, self.names)
 664
 665        return self.axes.flat[np.where(self.names == key)][0]
 666
 667    def draw(
 668        self,
 669        name: str,
 670        method: str,
 671        *args,
 672        **kwargs,
 673    ):
 674        """
 675        Implements drawing of other objects on the axis.
 676
 677        Parameters
 678        ----------
 679        name : str
 680            the name (label) of the parameter where we want to draw
 681
 682        method : str
 683            the name of the method which we want to plot (such as `plot`,
 684            `scatter`, etc.)
 685
 686        *args
 687            any positional arguments passed to the method (usually some data)
 688
 689        **kwargs
 690            any keyword arguments passed to the method (usually styling options)
 691
 692        Returns
 693        -------
 694        Artist
 695            the artist that was drawn on the figure
 696
 697        Raises
 698        ------
 699        EmptyFigureError
 700            if `plot` hasn't been called yet
 701        """
 702        if not hasattr(self[name], method):
 703            raise AttributeError(
 704                f"The method `{method}` is not a valid plotting method"
 705            )
 706
 707        # get the right color
 708        if "c" not in kwargs and "color" not in kwargs:
 709            kwargs["color"] = next(self.current_color)
 710            self.current_color = iter(self.current_color)
 711
 712        # hopefully the return type should be some artist, or a collection of
 713        # artists
 714        handles = getattr(self[name], method)(*args, **kwargs)
 715        if is_iterable(handles):
 716            for handle in handles:
 717                if isinstance(handle, Artist) and kwargs.get("label"):
 718                    self.labels.append(kwargs.get("label"))
 719                    self.handles.append(handle)
 720        else:
 721            if isinstance(handles, Artist) and kwargs.get("label"):
 722                self.labels.append(kwargs.get("label"))
 723                self.handles.append(handles)
 724
 725        self[name].autoscale()
 726        self[name].relim()
 727        self[name].autoscale_view()
 728
 729        return handles
 730
 731    def plot(
 732        self,
 733        fisher: FisherMatrix,
 734        *args,
 735        **kwargs,
 736    ):
 737        """
 738        Plots the 1D curves of the Fisher objects.
 739
 740        Parameters
 741        ----------
 742        fisher
 743            the Fisher object which we want to plot
 744
 745        **kwargs
 746            any keyword arguments used for plotting (same as `plot_curve_1d`)
 747
 748        Returns
 749        -------
 750        None
 751        """
 752        size = len(fisher)
 753
 754        added = False
 755
 756        # in order to preserve colors for each object, we only use the
 757        # (default) cycler when the color is not explicitly set
 758        if "c" not in kwargs and "color" not in kwargs:
 759            kwargs["color"] = next(self.current_color)
 760            self.current_color = iter(self.current_color)
 761
 762        if self.max_cols is not None and self.max_cols <= size:
 763            full = size % self.max_cols == 0
 764            layout = (
 765                size // self.max_cols if full else size // self.max_cols + 1,
 766                self.max_cols,
 767            )
 768        else:
 769            layout = 1, size
 770            full = True
 771
 772        with plt.rc_context(self.options):
 773            # general figure setup
 774            if self.figure:
 775                fig = self.figure
 776                axes = self.axes
 777            else:
 778                fig = plt.figure(
 779                    clear=True,
 780                    figsize=(2 * layout[1], 2 * layout[0]),
 781                )
 782                gs = fig.add_gridspec(
 783                    nrows=layout[0],
 784                    ncols=layout[1],
 785                    hspace=self.hspace,
 786                    wspace=self.wspace,
 787                )
 788                axes = gs.subplots()
 789                if size == 1:
 790                    axes = np.array([axes])
 791
 792            for (index, name), latex_name in zip(
 793                enumerate(fisher.names),
 794                fisher.latex_names,
 795            ):
 796                ax = axes.flat[index]
 797
 798                _, __, handle = plot_curve_1d(fisher, name, ax, **kwargs)
 799
 800                if not added and kwargs.get("label"):
 801                    self.handles.append(handle)
 802                    self.labels.append(kwargs["label"])
 803                    added = True
 804
 805                _add_shading_1d(
 806                    fisher.fiducials[np.where(fisher.names == name)],
 807                    fisher.constraints(name, marginalized=True),
 808                    ax,
 809                    alpha=0.3,
 810                    ec=None,
 811                    **kwargs,
 812                )
 813
 814                _add_shading_1d(
 815                    fisher.fiducials[np.where(fisher.names == name)],
 816                    fisher.constraints(name, marginalized=True),
 817                    ax,
 818                    level=2,
 819                    alpha=0.1,
 820                    ec=None,
 821                    **kwargs,
 822                )
 823
 824                ax.autoscale()
 825                ax.set_xlabel(latex_name)
 826                ax.relim()
 827                ax.autoscale_view()
 828
 829                # the y axis should start at 0 since we're plotting a PDF
 830                ax.set_ylim(0, ax.get_ylim()[-1])
 831
 832                ax.set_yticks([])
 833
 834            # remove any axes which are not drawn
 835            if not full:
 836                for index in range(
 837                    size,
 838                    layout[0] * layout[1],
 839                ):
 840                    # it's simpler to turn off the axis, than completely remove
 841                    # it
 842                    axes.flat[index].axis("off")
 843
 844        self._figure = fig
 845        self._axes = axes
 846        self._names = fisher.names
 847
 848    def legend(
 849        self,
 850        *args: Artist,
 851        overwrite: bool = False,
 852        loc: Union[str, tuple[float, float]] = "lower center",
 853        bbox_to_anchor: Any = [0.5, 1],
 854        **kwargs,
 855    ):
 856        """
 857        Creates a legend on the figure.
 858
 859        Parameters
 860        ----------
 861        *args
 862            any positional arguments for the legend
 863
 864        overwrite : bool, optional
 865            whether to overwrite any "nice" options set by `fitk` (default:
 866            False)
 867
 868        loc : str or tuple of floats, optional
 869            which corner of the legend to use as the positioning anchor
 870            (default: 'lower center')
 871
 872        bbox_to_anchor : Any, optional
 873            the location of where to place the legend (default: `[0.5, 1]`)
 874
 875        **kwargs
 876            any other keyword arguments for the legend
 877
 878        Returns
 879        -------
 880        Artist
 881            the legend that was drawn on the figure
 882
 883        Raises
 884        ------
 885        EmptyFigureError
 886            if `plot` hasn't been called yet
 887        """
 888        if not self.figure:
 889            raise EmptyFigureError
 890
 891        with plt.rc_context(self.options):
 892            ax = self.axes.flat[0]
 893            if not overwrite:
 894                if ax.get_legend():
 895                    ax.get_legend().remove()
 896
 897                return ax.legend(
 898                    self.handles,
 899                    self.labels,
 900                    loc=loc,
 901                    bbox_to_anchor=bbox_to_anchor,
 902                    bbox_transform=self.figure.transFigure,
 903                    **kwargs,
 904                )
 905
 906            return ax.legend(
 907                *args,
 908                loc=loc,
 909                bbox_to_anchor=bbox_to_anchor,
 910                **kwargs,
 911            )
 912
 913    def set_title(
 914        self,
 915        *args,
 916        x: float = 0.5,
 917        y: float = 1.2,
 918        **kwargs,
 919    ):
 920        """
 921        Thin wrapper for setting the title of the figure with the correct
 922        options.
 923
 924        Parameters
 925        ----------
 926        *args
 927            any positional arguments to `figure.suptitle`
 928
 929        x : float, optional
 930            the x position of the title (default: `0.5`)
 931
 932        y : float, optional
 933            the y position of the title (default: `1.2`)
 934
 935        **kwargs
 936            any keyword arguments to `figure.suptitle`
 937
 938        Returns
 939        -------
 940        Artist
 941            the title that was drawn on the figure
 942
 943        Raises
 944        ------
 945        EmptyFigureError
 946            if `plot` hasn't been called yet
 947        """
 948        if not self.figure:
 949            raise EmptyFigureError
 950
 951        with plt.rc_context(self.options):
 952            return self.figure.suptitle(*args, x=x, y=y, **kwargs)
 953
 954
 955class FisherFigure2D(FisherBaseFigure):
 956    r"""
 957    Container for easy access to elements in the 2D plot.
 958
 959    Examples
 960    --------
 961    Define some Fisher matrices:
 962    >>> m1 = FisherMatrix(
 963    ... [[3, -2], [-2, 5]],
 964    ... names=['a', 'b'],
 965    ... latex_names=[r'$\mathcal{A}$', r'$\mathcal{B}$'],
 966    ... )
 967    >>> m2 = FisherMatrix(
 968    ... [[4, 1], [1, 6]],
 969    ... names=['a', 'b'],
 970    ... latex_names=[r'$\mathcal{A}$', r'$\mathcal{B}$'],
 971    ... )
 972
 973    Instantiate a figure:
 974    >>> fig = FisherFigure2D(show_1d_curves=True)
 975
 976    Draw a "triangle plot" with the previously defined Fisher matrix:
 977    >>> fig.plot(m1, label='first')
 978
 979    Add a plot with a different color and style:
 980    >>> fig.plot(m2, label='second', ls=':', color='green')
 981
 982    Draw some other stuff on it:
 983    >>> artist, = fig.draw('a', 'b', 'plot', [-1, 0, 1], [-1, 0, 1], color='red')
 984    >>> # alternatively, the below will accomplish the same thing
 985    >>> # artist, = fig['a', 'b'].plot([-1, 0, 1], [-1, 0, 1], color='red')
 986
 987    Caveat: make sure to update the legend with this artist:
 988    >>> fig.add_artist_to_legend(artist, label='curve')
 989
 990    Add a legend:
 991    >>> _ = fig.legend()
 992
 993    Add a title:
 994    >>> _ = fig.set_title('Example Fisher matrix 2D plotting')
 995
 996    Save it to a file:
 997    >>> fig.savefig(
 998    ... Path(__file__).parent.parent / os.environ.get("TEMP_IMAGE_DIR") / "fisher_figure2d_example1.png",
 999    ... dpi=150)
1000

1002    """
1003
1004    def __init__(
1005        self,
1006        options: Optional[dict] = None,
1007        hspace: float = 0,
1008        wspace: float = 0,
1009        show_1d_curves: bool = False,
1010        show_joint_dist: bool = False,
1011    ):
1012        """
1013        Constructor.
1014
1015        Parameters
1016        ----------
1017        options : dict, optional
1018            the dictionary containing the options for plotting. If the special
1019            key 'style' is present, it attempts to use that plotting style (can
1020            be one of the outputs of `matplotlib.pyplot.style.available`, or a
1021            path to a file. If using a file, does not use the default rc
1022            parameters).
1023
1024        hspace : float, optional
1025            The amount of height reserved for space between subplots, expressed
1026            as a fraction of the average axis height.
1027
1028        wspace : float, optional
1029            The amount of width reserved for space between subplots, expressed
1030            as a fraction of the average axis width.
1031
1032        show_1d_curves : bool, optional
1033            whether the 1D marginalized curves should be plotted (default:
1034            False)
1035
1036        show_joint_dist : bool, optional
1037            whether to plot the isocontours of the joint distribution (default:
1038            False)
1039
1040        Notes
1041        -----
1042        For the style sheet reference, please consult [the matplotlib
1043        documentation](https://matplotlib.org/stable/gallery/style_sheets/style_sheets_reference.html).
1044
1045        **Regarding `show_joint_dist`**: this argument specifies whether we
1046        wish to plot the p-value of the *joint* distribution, or the p-value of
1047        the probability of a single parameter lying within the bounds projected
1048        onto a parameter axis. For more details, see
1049        [arXiv:0906.0664](https://arxiv.org/abs/0906.0664), section 2.
1050        """
1051        super().__init__(options=options, wspace=wspace, hspace=hspace)
1052        self.show_1d_curves = show_1d_curves
1053        self.show_joint_dist = show_joint_dist
1054        self._ndim = 2
1055
1056    def __getitem__(
1057        self,
1058        key: tuple[str, str],
1059    ):
1060        if not self.figure:
1061            raise EmptyFigureError
1062
1063        if not isinstance(key, tuple):
1064            raise TypeError(
1065                f"Incompatible type for element access: expected `tuple`, got `{type(key)}`"
1066            )
1067
1068        name1, name2 = key
1069
1070        if name1 not in self.names:
1071            raise ParameterNotFoundError(name1, self.names)
1072        if name2 not in self.names:
1073            raise ParameterNotFoundError(name2, self.names)
1074
1075        # edge case
1076        if not self.show_1d_curves and name1 == name2:
1077            return None
1078
1079        index1 = np.where(self.names == name1)
1080        index2 = np.where(self.names == name2)
1081
1082        if index1 < index2:
1083            index1, index2 = index2, index1
1084
1085        return self.axes[index1, index2][0, 0]
1086
1087    def legend(
1088        self,
1089        *args: Artist,
1090        overwrite: bool = False,
1091        loc: Union[str, tuple[float, float]] = "upper right",
1092        bbox_to_anchor: Optional[Any] = None,
1093        **kwargs,
1094    ):
1095        """
1096        Creates a legend on the figure.
1097
1098        Parameters
1099        ----------
1100        *args
1101            any positional arguments for the legend
1102
1103        overwrite : bool, optional
1104            whether to overwrite any "nice" options set by `fitk` (default:
1105            False)
1106
1107        loc : str or tuple of floats, optional
1108            which corner of the legend to use as the positioning anchor
1109            (default: 'upper right')
1110
1111        bbox_to_anchor : Any, optional
1112            the location of where to place the legend (default: None, picked by
1113            `fitk` based on information about the plot)
1114
1115        **kwargs
1116            any other keyword arguments for the legend
1117
1118        Returns
1119        -------
1120        Artist
1121            the legend that was drawn on the figure
1122
1123        Raises
1124        ------
1125        EmptyFigureError
1126            if `plot` hasn't been called yet
1127        """
1128        if not self.figure:
1129            raise EmptyFigureError
1130
1131        with plt.rc_context(self.options):
1132            # this will always exist since we can't plot < 2 parameters
1133            ax = self[self.names[0], self.names[1]]
1134            if not overwrite:
1135                if self.show_1d_curves:
1136                    i, j = 0, -1
1137                else:
1138                    i, j = 1, -2
1139
1140                bbox_to_anchor = (
1141                    self.axes[0, j].get_position().xmax,
1142                    self.axes[i, 0].get_position().ymax,
1143                )
1144
1145                if ax.get_legend():
1146                    ax.get_legend().remove()
1147
1148                return ax.legend(
1149                    self.handles,
1150                    self.labels,
1151                    loc=loc,
1152                    bbox_to_anchor=bbox_to_anchor,
1153                    bbox_transform=self.figure.transFigure,
1154                    **kwargs,
1155                )
1156
1157            return ax.legend(
1158                *args,
1159                loc=loc,
1160                bbox_to_anchor=bbox_to_anchor,
1161                **kwargs,
1162            )
1163
1164    def set_title(
1165        self,
1166        *args,
1167        overwrite: bool = False,
1168        xscale: float = 0.5,
1169        yscale: float = 1.08,
1170        **kwargs,
1171    ):
1172        """
1173        Thin wrapper for setting the title of the figure with the correct
1174        options.
1175
1176        Parameters
1177        ----------
1178        *args
1179            any positional arguments to `figure.suptitle`
1180
1181        xscale : float, optional
1182            the x position of the title (default: `0.5`)
1183
1184        yscale : float, optional
1185            the y position of the title (default: `1.08`)
1186
1187        **kwargs
1188            any keyword arguments to `figure.suptitle`
1189
1190        Returns
1191        -------
1192        Artist
1193            the title that was drawn on the figure
1194
1195        Raises
1196        ------
1197        EmptyFigureError
1198            if `plot` hasn't been called yet
1199        """
1200        if not self.figure:
1201            raise EmptyFigureError
1202
1203        with plt.rc_context(self.options):
1204            if not overwrite:
1205                if self.show_1d_curves:
1206                    i, j = 0, -1
1207                else:
1208                    i, j = 1, -2
1209
1210                x, y = (
1211                    self.axes[0, j].get_position().xmax,
1212                    self.axes[i, 0].get_position().ymax,
1213                )
1214
1215                return self.figure.suptitle(
1216                    *args,
1217                    x=x * xscale,
1218                    y=y * yscale,
1219                    **kwargs,
1220                )
1221
1222            return self.figure.suptitle(*args, **kwargs)
1223
1224    def draw(
1225        self,
1226        name1: str,
1227        name2: str,
1228        method: str,
1229        *args,
1230        **kwargs,
1231    ):
1232        """
1233        Implements drawing of other objects on the axis.
1234
1235        Parameters
1236        ----------
1237        name1 : str
1238            the name (label) of the first parameter where we want to draw
1239
1240        name2 : str
1241            the name (label) of the second parameter where we want to draw
1242
1243        method : str
1244            the name of the method which we want to plot (such as `plot`,
1245            `scatter`, etc.)
1246
1247        *args
1248            any positional arguments passed to the method (usually some data)
1249
1250        **kwargs
1251            any keyword arguments passed to the method (usually styling options)
1252
1253        Returns
1254        -------
1255        Artist
1256            the artist that was drawn on the figure
1257
1258        Raises
1259        ------
1260        EmptyFigureError
1261            if `plot` hasn't been called yet
1262        """
1263        if not hasattr(self[name1, name2], method):
1264            raise AttributeError(
1265                f"The method `{method}` is not a valid plotting method"
1266            )
1267
1268        # get the right color
1269        if "c" not in kwargs and "color" not in kwargs:
1270            kwargs["color"] = next(self.current_color)
1271            self.current_color = iter(self.current_color)
1272
1273        with plt.rc_context(self.options):
1274            # hopefully the return type should be some artist, or a collection
1275            # of artists
1276            handles = getattr(self[name1, name2], method)(*args, **kwargs)
1277            if is_iterable(handles):
1278                for handle in handles:
1279                    if isinstance(handle, Artist) and kwargs.get("label"):
1280                        self.labels.append(kwargs["label"])
1281                        self.handles.append(handle)
1282            else:
1283                if isinstance(handles, Artist) and kwargs.get("label"):
1284                    self.labels.append(kwargs["label"])
1285                    self.handles.append(handles)
1286
1287        self[name1, name2].autoscale()
1288        self[name1, name2].relim()
1289        self[name1, name2].autoscale_view()
1290
1291        return handles
1292
1293    def plot(
1294        self,
1295        fisher: FisherMatrix,
1296        *args,
1297        **kwargs,
1298    ):
1299        r"""
1300        Plots the 2D contours (and optionally 1D curves) of the Fisher objects.
1301
1302        Parameters
1303        ----------
1304        fisher : FisherMatrix
1305            the Fisher object which we want to plot
1306
1307        **kwargs
1308            any keyword arguments used for plotting (same as `plot_curve_2d`)
1309
1310        Returns
1311        -------
1312        None
1313
1314        Examples
1315        --------
1316        Define a Fisher matrix:
1317        >>> m = FisherMatrix([[3, -2], [-2, 5]], names=['a', 'b'], latex_names=[r'$\mathcal{A}$', r'$\mathcal{B}$'])
1318
1319        Initiate a figure:
1320        >>> fig = FisherFigure2D(show_1d_curves=True)

2+/HdHR0Xj99df5y40PUUtdAJGve/jhh/HMM89Aq9VCo9FIXQ6RTzt8+DAA4K677nIEpcrKSrzzzjv46quv8Nhjj2H58uVSlkgSYCwmktDnn3+O2tpax5C+VquF2WyWuCoi33XgwAEAwP3334/CwkJcdtllGDduHH71q18hIyMDEyZMkLhCkgKn4Ygk0tLSgtzcXHzxxRfIyckBAGRkZKC9vR1NTU0SV0fkmyIiIhAZGYmioiJs2rQJTU1NqKysxAcffID8/HxoNBr8+9//xjXXXCN1qeRGDEtEErnllluQnp6O3//+946vzZgxAwUFBTCZTFAoFBJWR+R7Tp48iczMTDz22GN4+eWXB9wnCAJ++tOf4pVXXkFiYiKqq6slqpKkwGk4Ign885//xKFDh/CLX/wCZrPZ8SckJARmsxltbW1Sl0jkczZu3AgAg44aKRQKvPDCC4iOjkZNTQ1Hf30MG7yJ3OzgwYN46KGHEBQUhODgYAw2uFtRUYHw8HAJqiPyXRs2bEBkZCQWLVo06P0ajQZpaWno7Ozk69PHMCwRuZggCI4ptdbWVixbtgw/+tGPsHLlyjMe++KLL+Kjjz5CXl4ecnNz3Vwpke8yGo347rvvcNNNN0GlUg36GLPZjLKyMtxzzz1nfQx5J07DEblQVVUVFi5ciKKiItTW1uKqq67C+PHj8corr2DWrFln/DnvvPMAAN9++63ElRP5li+++AJ6vR6LFy/GW2+9NeiI7wsvvICUlBS88MILElRIUmKDN5EL/fe//8X111/vOF60aBG+/PJLBAcHD/r4Xbt24bzzzoO/vz+WL1+OyZMn46mnnnJXuUQ+67LLLkNTUxNKSkrQ3t6OxYsX47777kNMTAwqKyvxySefIC4uDn/6058QEBAgdbnkZgxLRC5kMplw11134csvv8SNN96IV199dcg3WovFgtmzZ6Ourg5PP/00HnroIa4STORix44dw913341//etfqK+vxy9/+UscPHgQarUaEydOxOLFi3HPPfdg0qRJUpdKEmFYIiIiIhoCf2UlIiIiGgLDEhEREdEQGJaIiIiIhsCwRERERDQEhiUiIiKiITAsEREREQ2BYYmIiIhoCAxLRERERENgWCIiIiIaAsMSERER0RAYloiIiIiGwLBERERENASGJSIiIqIhMCwRERERDYFhiYiIiGgIDEtEREREQ2BYIiIiIhrC/wfvZLwxvzVsbgAAAABJRU5ErkJggg=="
1331        """
1332        size = len(fisher)
1333
1334        if size < 2:
1335            raise ValueError("Unable to make a 2D plot with < 2 parameters")
1336
1337        if self.names is not None:
1338            # make sure they have the same names; if not, raise an error
1339            if set(self.names) != set(fisher.names):
1340                raise ValueError(
1341                    f"The Fisher object names ({fisher.names}) "
1342                    f"do not match those on the figure ({self.names})"
1343                )
1344
1345            # otherwise, we reshuffle them
1346            fisher = fisher.sort(key=self.names)
1347
1348        # in order to preserve colors for each object, we only use the
1349        # (default) cycler when the color is not explicitly set
1350        if "c" not in kwargs and "color" not in kwargs:
1351            kwargs["color"] = next(self.current_color)
1352            self.current_color = iter(self.current_color)
1353
1354        with plt.rc_context(self.options):
1355            # general figure setup
1356            if self.figure:
1357                fig = self.figure
1358                ax = self.axes
1359            else:
1360                fig = plt.figure(
1361                    figsize=(2 * size, 2 * size),
1362                    clear=True,
1363                )
1364                ax = fig.add_gridspec(
1365                    nrows=size,
1366                    ncols=size,
1367                    hspace=self.hspace,
1368                    wspace=self.wspace,
1369                ).subplots(
1370                    sharex="col",
1371                    sharey=False,
1372                )
1373
1374            # set automatic limits
1375            for i, j in product(range(size), repeat=2):
1376                if i == j:
1377                    ax[i, i].set_yticks([])
1378                    ax[i, i].set_yticklabels([])
1379                    if i < size - 1:
1380                        ax[i, i].get_xaxis().set_visible(False)
1381                if i > 0 and 0 < j < size - 1:
1382                    ax[i, j].set_yticks([])
1383                    ax[i, j].set_yticklabels([])
1384                if i > j and i != size - 1:
1385                    ax[i, j].get_xaxis().set_visible(False)
1386
1387            # flag for whether the current artist has already been added to the
1388            # legend handle
1389            added = False
1390            # loop over the parameters
1391            for i, j in product(range(len(fisher.names)), repeat=2):
1392                namey, latex_namey, namex, latex_namex = (
1393                    fisher.names[i],
1394                    fisher.latex_names[i],
1395                    fisher.names[j],
1396                    fisher.latex_names[j],
1397                )
1398                # labels for 2D contours (increasing y)
1399                if i > 0 and j == 0:
1400                    ax[i, j].set_ylabel(latex_namey)
1401
1402                # labels for 2D contours (increasing x)
1403                if i == size - 1:
1404                    ax[i, j].set_xlabel(latex_namex)
1405
1406                # removing any unnecessary axes from the gridspec
1407                if i < j and self.figure is None:
1408                    # calling `remove()` is better than `axis("off")` because
1409                    # then we obtain the proper bounding box
1410                    ax[i, j].remove()
1411
1412                # plotting the 2D contours
1413                elif i > j:
1414                    # plot 1-sigma 2D curves
1415                    # NOTE this is the "68% of the probability of a
1416                    # single parameter lying within the bounds projected
1417                    # onto a parameter axis"
1418                    _, __, handle = plot_curve_2d(
1419                        fisher,
1420                        namex,
1421                        namey,
1422                        ax=ax[i, j],
1423                        scaling_factor=1
1424                        if not self.show_joint_dist
1425                        else np.sqrt(_get_chisq(1)),
1426                        fill=False,
1427                        zorder=20,
1428                        **kwargs,
1429                    )
1430
1431                    if not added and kwargs.get("label"):
1432                        self.handles.append(handle)
1433                        self.labels.append(kwargs["label"])
1434                        added = True
1435
1436                    # same thing, but shaded
1437                    plot_curve_2d(
1438                        fisher,
1439                        namex,
1440                        namey,
1441                        ax=ax[i, j],
1442                        scaling_factor=1
1443                        if not self.show_joint_dist
1444                        else np.sqrt(_get_chisq(1)),
1445                        fill=True,
1446                        alpha=0.2,
1447                        ec=None,
1448                        zorder=20,
1449                        **kwargs,
1450                    )
1451
1452                    # the 2-sigma
1453                    plot_curve_2d(
1454                        fisher,
1455                        namex,
1456                        namey,
1457                        ax=ax[i, j],
1458                        scaling_factor=2
1459                        if not self.show_joint_dist
1460                        else np.sqrt(_get_chisq(2)),
1461                        fill=False,
1462                        zorder=20,
1463                        **kwargs,
1464                    )
1465                    # same thing, but shaded
1466                    plot_curve_2d(
1467                        fisher,
1468                        namex,
1469                        namey,
1470                        ax=ax[i, j],
1471                        scaling_factor=2
1472                        if not self.show_joint_dist
1473                        else np.sqrt(_get_chisq(2)),
1474                        fill=True,
1475                        alpha=0.1,
1476                        ec=None,
1477                        zorder=20,
1478                        **kwargs,
1479                    )
1480
1481                if i == j:
1482                    # plotting the 1D Gaussians
1483                    if self.show_1d_curves is True:
1484                        plot_curve_1d(
1485                            fisher,
1486                            namex,
1487                            ax=ax[i, i],
1488                            **kwargs,
1489                        )
1490
1491                    else:
1492                        if self.figure is None:
1493                            ax[i, i].remove()
1494
1495            # set automatic limits
1496            for i, j in product(range(size), repeat=2):
1497                try:
1498                    ax[i, j].relim()
1499                    ax[i, j].autoscale_view()
1500                    if i == j:
1501                        ax[i, i].autoscale()
1502                        ax[i, i].set_ylim(0, ax[i, i].get_ylim()[-1])
1503                        ax[i, i].set_yticks([])
1504                        ax[i, i].set_yticklabels([])
1505                except AttributeError:
1506                    pass
1507
1508        self._figure = fig
1509        self._axes = ax
1510        self._names = fisher.names
1511
1512
1513def _get_chisq(
1514    sigma: float = 1,
1515    df: int = 2,
1516):
1517    r"""
1518    Returns $\Delta \chi^2$.
1519    To obtain the scaling coefficient $\alpha$, just take the square root of
1520    the output.
1521
1522    Parameters
1523    ----------
1524    sigma : float = 1
1525        the error on the parameter
1526
1527    df : int = 2
1528        the number of degrees of freedom
1529
1530    Returns
1531    -------
1532    float
1533    """
1534    return chi2.ppf(norm.cdf(sigma) - norm.cdf(-sigma), df=df)
1535
1536
1537def _add_plot_1d(
1538    fiducial: float,
1539    sigma: float,
1540    ax: Optional[Axes] = None,
1541    **kwargs,
1542) -> tuple[Figure, Axes, Artist]:
1543    """
1544    Adds a 1D Gaussian with marginalized constraints `sigma` close to fiducial
1545    value `fiducial` to axis `ax`.
1546    """
1547    if ax is None:
1548        _, ax = plt.subplots()
1549
1550    x = np.linspace(
1551        fiducial - 4 * sigma,
1552        fiducial + 4 * sigma,
1553        100,
1554    )
1555
1556    (handle,) = ax.plot(
1557        x,
1558        [norm.pdf(_, loc=fiducial, scale=sigma) for _ in x],
1559        **kwargs,
1560    )
1561
1562    return (ax.get_figure(), ax, handle)
1563
1564
1565def _add_shading_1d(
1566    fiducial: float,
1567    sigma: float,
1568    ax: Optional[Axes] = None,
1569    level: float = 1,
1570    **kwargs,
1571) -> tuple[Figure, Axes]:
1572    """
1573    Add shading to a 1D axes.
1574    """
1575    if ax is None:
1576        _, ax = plt.subplots()
1577
1578    x = np.ndarray.flatten(
1579        np.linspace(
1580            fiducial - level * sigma,
1581            fiducial + level * sigma,
1582            100,
1583        )
1584    )
1585
1586    ax.fill_between(
1587        x,
1588        np.ndarray.flatten(
1589            np.array([norm.pdf(_, loc=fiducial, scale=sigma) for _ in x])
1590        ),
1591        **kwargs,
1592    )
1593
1594    return (ax.get_figure(), ax)
1595
1596
1597def plot_curve_1d(
1598    fisher: FisherMatrix,
1599    name: str,
1600    ax: Optional[Axes] = None,
1601    **kwargs,
1602) -> tuple[Figure, Axes, Artist]:
1603    r"""
1604    Plots a 1D curve (usually marginalized Gaussian) from a Fisher object.
1605
1606    Parameters
1607    ----------
1608    fisher : FisherMatrix
1609        the Fisher matrix which we want to plot
1610
1611    name : str
1612        the name of the parameter which we want to plot
1613
1614    ax : matplotlib.axes.Axes, optional
1615        the axis on which we want to plot the contour (default: None). If None,
1616        plots to a new figure.
1617
1618    **kwargs
1619        any keyword arguments passed to `matplotlib.pyplot.plot`
1620
1621    Returns
1622    -------
1623    A 3-tuple `(Figure, Axes, Artist)`
1624        The figure and the axis on which the artist was drawn on, as well as
1625        the artist itself.
1626
1627    Examples
1628    --------
1629    Define a Fisher matrix:
1630    >>> m = FisherMatrix(
1631    ... [[3, -2], [-2, 5]],
1632    ... names=['a', 'b'],
1633    ... latex_names=[r'$\mathcal{A}$', r'$\mathcal{B}$'],
1634    ... )
1635
1636    Draw the marginalized parameter `a`:
1637    >>> fig, ax, artist = plot_curve_1d(m, name='a', ls='--', color='red')
1638
1639    Save it to a file:
1640    >>> fig.savefig(
1641    ... Path(__file__).parent.parent / os.environ.get("TEMP_IMAGE_DIR") / "plot_curve_1d_example1.png",
1642    ... dpi=100)

1645    """
1646    if ax is None:
1647        _, ax = plt.subplots()
1648
1649    fid = fisher.fiducials[np.where(fisher.names == name)]
1650    sigma = fisher.constraints(name, marginalized=True)
1651
1652    return _add_plot_1d(fid, sigma, ax=ax, **kwargs)
1653
1654
1655def plot_curve_2d(
1656    fisher: FisherMatrix,
1657    name1: str,
1658    name2: str,
1659    ax: Optional[Axes] = None,
1660    scaling_factor: float = 1,
1661    **kwargs,
1662) -> tuple[Figure, Axes, Artist]:
1663    r"""
1664    Plots a 2D curve (usually ellipse) from two parameters of a Fisher object.
1665
1666    Parameters
1667    ----------
1668    fisher : FisherMatrix
1669        the Fisher matrix which we want to plot
1670
1671    name1 : str
1672        the name of the first parameter which we want to plot
1673
1674    name2 : str
1675        the name of the second parameter which we want to plot
1676
1677    ax : matplotlib.axes.Axes, optional
1678        the axis on which we want to plot the contour (default: None). If None,
1679        plots to a new figure.
1680
1681    **kwargs
1682        any keyword arguments passed to `matplotlib.patches.Ellipse`
1683
1684    Returns
1685    -------
1686    A 3-tuple `(Figure, Axes, Artist)`
1687        The figure and the axis on which the artist was drawn on, as well as
1688        the artist itself.
1689
1690    Examples
1691    --------
1692    Define a Fisher matrix:
1693    >>> m = FisherMatrix(
1694    ... [[3, -2], [-2, 5]],
1695    ... names=['a', 'b'],
1696    ... fiducials=[1, -2],
1697    ... latex_names=[r'$\mathcal{A}$', r'$\mathcal{B}$'],
1698    ... )
1699
1700    Draw the 1$\sigma$ contour of the parameter combination `a`, `b`:
1701    >>> fig, ax, artist = plot_curve_2d(m, name1='a', name2='b', ls='--', color='red', fill=False)
1702
1703    Rescale the view a bit:
1704    >>> _ = ax.autoscale()
1705    >>> _ = ax.relim()
1706    >>> _ = ax.autoscale_view()
1707
1708    Save it to a file:
1709    >>> fig.savefig(
1710    ... Path(__file__).parent.parent / os.environ.get("TEMP_IMAGE_DIR") / "plot_curve_2d_example1.png",
1711    ... dpi=100)

AQMARAAACBgCIAAAAABQwAEAAAIGAIgAABAwBAAAQAAAoYACAAAEDAEQAAAgIAhAAIAAAQMARAAACBgCIAAAAABQwAEAAAIGAIgAABAwBAAAQAAAoYACAAAEDAEQAAAgIAhAAIAAAQMARAAACBgCIAAAAABQwAEAAAImP8DRx0aJ3sVAw0AAAAASUVORK5CYII="
1714
1715    Notes
1716    -----
1717    The limits of the plot are not updated automatically.
1718    """
1719    if ax is None:
1720        _, ax = plt.subplots()
1721
1722    fidx = fisher.fiducials[np.where(fisher.names == name1)]
1723    fidy = fisher.fiducials[np.where(fisher.names == name2)]
1724
1725    a, b, angle = _get_ellipse(fisher, name1, name2)
1726
1727    patch = ax.add_patch(
1728        Ellipse(
1729            xy=(fidx, fidy),
1730            width=2 * a * scaling_factor,
1731            height=2 * b * scaling_factor,
1732            angle=angle,
1733            **kwargs,
1734        ),
1735    )
1736
1737    return (ax.get_figure(), ax, patch)
1738
1739
1740def _get_ellipse(
1741    fm: FisherMatrix,
1742    name1: str,
1743    name2: str,
1744) -> tuple[float, float, float]:
1745    """
1746    Constructs parameters for a Gaussian ellipse from the names.
1747    """
1748    if name1 == name2:
1749        raise ValueError("Names must be different")
1750
1751    # the inverse
1752    inv = FisherMatrix(fm.inverse(), names=fm.names)
1753
1754    sigmax2 = inv[name1, name1]
1755    sigmay2 = inv[name2, name2]
1756    sigmaxy = inv[name1, name2]
1757
1758    # basically the eigenvalues of the submatrix
1759    a = np.sqrt(
1760        (sigmax2 + sigmay2) / 2 + np.sqrt((sigmax2 - sigmay2) ** 2 / 4 + sigmaxy**2)
1761    )
1762
1763    b = np.sqrt(
1764        (sigmax2 + sigmay2) / 2 - np.sqrt((sigmax2 - sigmay2) ** 2 / 4 + sigmaxy**2)
1765    )
1766
1767    angle = np.rad2deg(
1768        np.arctan2(
1769            2 * sigmaxy,
1770            sigmax2 - sigmay2,
1771        )
1772        / 2
1773    )
1774
1775    return a, b, angle

class FisherBaseFigure(abc.ABC): 
 45class FisherBaseFigure(ABC):
 46    """
 47    The abstract base class for plotting Fisher objects.
 48    """
 49
 50    def __init__(
 51        self,
 52        *args,
 53        options: Optional[dict] = None,
 54        hspace: float = 0.1,
 55        wspace: float = 0.1,
 56        **kwargs,
 57    ):
 58        """
 59        Constructor
 60        """
 61        self._figure = None
 62        self._axes = None
 63        self._handles: MutableSequence[Artist] = []
 64        self._names = None
 65        self._labels: MutableSequence[str] = []
 66        self._options: dict = get_default_rcparams()
 67        self._ndim: int = 0
 68        self._hspace = hspace
 69        self._wspace = wspace
 70
 71        self.cycler = plt.rcParams["axes.prop_cycle"].by_key()["color"]
 72        self.current_color = iter(self.cycler)
 73
 74        if options and "style" in options:
 75            style = options.pop("style")
 76            # maybe it's one of the built-in styles
 77            if style in plt.style.available:
 78                self._options = {
 79                    **plt.style.library[style],
 80                    **get_default_rcparams(),
 81                    **options,
 82                }
 83                # we need to reset the color cycler
 84                self.cycler = (
 85                    plt.style.library[style]
 86                    .get(
 87                        "axes.prop_cycle",
 88                        plt.rcParams["axes.prop_cycle"],
 89                    )
 90                    .by_key()["color"]
 91                )
 92                self.current_color = iter(self.cycler)
 93
 94            # maybe it's a file
 95            else:
 96                # we need to reset the color cycler
 97                self.cycler = (
 98                    plt.style.core.rc_params_from_file(style)
 99                    .get(
100                        "axes.prop_cycle",
101                        plt.rcParams["axes.prop_cycle"],
102                    )
103                    .by_key()["color"]
104                )
105                self.current_color = iter(self.cycler)
106
107                self._options = {
108                    **plt.style.core.rc_params_from_file(style),
109                    **options,
110                }

112    @abstractmethod
113    def plot(self, fisher: FisherMatrix, *args, **kwargs):
114        """
115        Implements plotting of Fisher objects.
116        """
117        return NotImplemented
118
119    @abstractmethod
120    def __getitem__(self, key):
121        """
122        Implements element access.
123        """
124        return NotImplemented

126    @property
127    def figure(self):
128        """
129        Returns the underlying figure, an instance of
130        `matplotlib.figure.Figure`.
131        """
132        return self._figure
133
134    @property
135    def axes(self):
136        """
137        Returns the axes of the figure as a numpy array.
138        """
139        return self._axes
140
141    @property
142    def hspace(self) -> float:
143        """
144        The amount of height reserved for space between subplots, expressed as
145        a fraction of the average axis height.
146        """
147        return self._hspace
148
149    @property
150    def wspace(self) -> float:
151        """
152        The amount of width reserved for space between subplots, expressed as a
153        fraction of the average axis width.
154        """
155        return self._wspace
156
157    @property
158    def names(self):
159        """
160        Returns the names of the original parameters plotted.
161        """
162        return self._names
163
164    @property
165    def handles(self):
166        """
167        Returns the handles of the currently drawn artists.
168        """
169        return self._handles
170
171    @property
172    def labels(self):
173        """
174        Returns the legend labels of the currently drawn artists.
175        """
176        return self._labels
177
178    @property
179    def options(self):
180        """
181        Returns the matplotlib options which were used for plotting.
182        """
183        return self._options
184
185    def __repr__(self):
186        """
187        Returns the representation of the figure
188        """
189        return (
190            f"<FisherFigure(\n"
191            f"    names={repr(self.names)},\n"
192            f"    figure={repr(self.figure)},\n"
193            f"    axes={repr(self.axes)})>"
194        )

197        """

201            f"FisherFigure(\n"
202            f"    names={str(self.names)},\n"
203            f"    figure={str(self.figure)},\n"
204            f"    axes={str(self.axes)})"
205        )
206
207    def add_artist_to_legend(
208        self,
209        artist: Artist,
210        label: str,
211    ):
212        r"""
213        This is a convenience function for correctly updating the legend after
214        directly plotting some artist via `<instance>[<name(s)>].<method>`
215
216        Parameters
217        ----------
218        artist
219            the artist which we want to put on the legend
220
221        label : str
222            the label for the artist
223
224        Returns
225        -------
226        None
227
228        Examples
229        --------
230        Setup the plot:
231        >>> fig = FisherFigure1D()
232        >>> fig.plot(FisherMatrix(np.diag([1, 2]), names=["a", "b"]), label="Fisher matrix")
233
234        Add something to the plot that has a handle:
235        >>> handle, = fig["a"].plot([-1, 0, 1], [-1, 0, 1], color='red')
236
237        Finally, add the handle to the legend, and draw the legend:
238        >>> fig.add_artist_to_legend(handle, "linear function")
239        >>> _ = fig.legend() # the artist will now be shown correctly in the legend
240
241        Save it to a file:
242        >>> fig.savefig(
243        ... Path(__file__).parent.parent / os.environ.get("TEMP_IMAGE_DIR") / "fisher_figure2d_add_artist_to_legend1.png",
244        ... dpi=150)
245

247
248        Notes
249        -----
250        The limits of the plot are not updated automatically.
251        """
252        self.labels.append(label)
253        self.handles.append(artist)
254
255    def savefig(
256        self,
257        path: Path,
258        dpi: float = 300,
259        bbox_inches: Union[str, Bbox] = "tight",
260        **kwargs,
261    ):
262        """
263        Convenience wrapper for `figure.savefig`.
264
265        Parameters
266        ----------
267        path : Path
268            the path where to save the figure
269
270        dpi : float, optional
271            the resolution of the saved figure (default: 300)
272
273        bbox_inches : str or Bbox, optional
274            what is the bounding box for the figure (default: 'tight')
275
276        **kwargs
277            any other keyword arguments that should be passed to
278            `figure.savefig`
279
280        Returns
281        -------
282        None
283
284        Raises
285        ------
286        EmptyFigureError
287            if `plot` hasn't been called yet
288        """
289        if not self.figure:
290            raise EmptyFigureError
291
292        self.figure.savefig(
293            path,
294            dpi=dpi,
295            bbox_inches=bbox_inches,
296            **kwargs,
297        )
298
299    def set_label_params(
300        self,
301        which: str = "both",
302        **kwargs,
303    ):
304        """
305        Collectively sets both x and y label parameters.
306
307        Parameters
308        ----------
309        which : {'both', 'x', 'y'}
310            which axis to change (default: 'both')
311
312        **kwargs
313            any keyword arguments that are also valid for
314            `matplotlib.text.Text`, see [the
315            documentation](https://matplotlib.org/stable/api/text_api.html#matplotlib.text.Text)
316            for details
317
318        Returns
319        -------
320        None
321
322        Raises
323        ------
324        EmptyFigureError
325            if `plot` hasn't been called yet
326        """
327        if not self.figure:
328            raise EmptyFigureError
329
330        for nameiter in product(self.names, repeat=self._ndim):
331            # only set the parameters which are not empty (should this be done
332            # for all of them instead?)
333            if (
334                self[nameiter]
335                and self[nameiter].get_xlabel()
336                and which in ["both", "x"]
337            ):
338                self[nameiter].set_xlabel(
339                    self[nameiter].get_xlabel(),
340                    **kwargs,
341                )
342            if (
343                self[nameiter]
344                and self[nameiter].get_ylabel()
345                and which in ["both", "y"]
346            ):
347                self[nameiter].set_ylabel(
348                    self[nameiter].get_ylabel(),
349                    **kwargs,
350                )
351
352    def set_tick_params(
353        self,
354        which: str = "both",
355        **kwargs,
356    ):
357        """
358        Collectively sets both x and y tick parameters.
359
360        Parameters
361        ----------
362        which : {'both', 'x', 'y'}
363            which axis to change (default: 'both')
364
365        **kwargs
366            any keyword arguments passed to the methods for handling tick
367            parameters (such as 'fontsize', 'rotation', etc.)
368
369        Returns
370        -------
371        None
372
373        Raises
374        ------
375        EmptyFigureError
376            if `plot` hasn't been called yet
377        """
378        if not self.figure:
379            raise EmptyFigureError
380
381        for nameiter in product(self.names, repeat=self._ndim):
382            if self[nameiter] and which in ["both", "x"]:
383                for item in self[nameiter].get_xticklabels():
384                    for key, value in kwargs.items():
385                        getattr(item, f"set_{key}")(value)
386            if self[nameiter] and which in ["both", "y"]:
387                for item in self[nameiter].get_yticklabels():
388                    for key, value in kwargs.items():
389                        getattr(item, f"set_{key}")(value)
390            # also alter any exponential offsets
391            for key, value in kwargs.items():
392                if self[nameiter] and which in ["both", "x"]:
393                    getattr(
394                        self[nameiter].get_xaxis().get_offset_text(),
395                        f"set_{key}",
396                    )(value)
397                if self[nameiter] and which in ["both", "y"]:
398                    getattr(
399                        self[nameiter].get_yaxis().get_offset_text(),
400                        f"set_{key}",
401                    )(value)
402
403    def set_major_locator(
404        self,
405        locator: Locator,
406        which: str = "both",
407    ):
408        """
409        Sets the major locator for all of the axes.
410
411        Parameters
412        ----------
413        locator
414            the instance of `matplotlib.ticker.Locator` to use.
415
416        which : {'both', 'x', 'y'}
417            which axis to change (default: 'both')
418
419        Returns
420        -------
421        None
422
423        Raises
424        ------
425        EmptyFigureError
426            if `plot` hasn't been called yet
427        """
428        if not self.figure:
429            raise EmptyFigureError
430
431        for nameiter in product(self.names, repeat=self._ndim):
432            # for some reason, we cannot reuse the same instance, so we just
433            # make a deep copy of it instead
434            if (
435                self[nameiter]
436                and np.any(self[nameiter].get_xticks())
437                and which in ["both", "x"]
438            ):
439                xloc = copy.deepcopy(locator)
440                self[nameiter].xaxis.set_major_locator(xloc)
441            if (
442                self[nameiter]
443                and np.any(self[nameiter].get_yticks())
444                and which in ["both", "y"]
445            ):
446                yloc = copy.deepcopy(locator)
447                self[nameiter].yaxis.set_major_locator(yloc)
448
449    def set_minor_locator(
450        self,
451        locator: Locator,
452        which: str = "both",
453    ):
454        """
455        Sets the minor locator for all of the axes.
456
457        Parameters
458        ----------
459        locator
460            the instance of `matplotlib.ticker.Locator` to use.
461
462        which : {'both', 'x', 'y'}
463            which axis to change (default: 'both')
464
465        Returns
466        -------
467        None
468
469        Raises
470        ------
471        EmptyFigureError
472            if `plot` hasn't been called yet
473        """
474        if not self.figure:
475            raise EmptyFigureError
476
477        for nameiter in product(self.names, repeat=self._ndim):
478            if (
479                self[nameiter]
480                and np.any(self[nameiter].get_xticks())
481                and which in ["both", "x"]
482            ):
483                # same reason as the major locator
484                xloc = copy.deepcopy(locator)
485                self[nameiter].xaxis.set_minor_locator(xloc)
486            if (
487                self[nameiter]
488                and np.any(self[nameiter].get_yticks())
489                and which in ["both", "y"]
490            ):
491                yloc = copy.deepcopy(locator)
492                self[nameiter].yaxis.set_minor_locator(yloc)
493
494    def set_major_formatter(
495        self,
496        formatter: Formatter,
497        which: str = "both",
498    ):
499        """
500        Sets the major formatter for all of the axes.
501
502        Parameters
503        ----------
504        formatter
505            the instance of `matplotlib.ticker.Formatter` to use.
506
507        which : {'both', 'x', 'y'}
508            which axis to change (default: 'both')
509
510        Returns
511        -------
512        None
513
514        Raises
515        ------
516        EmptyFigureError
517            if `plot` hasn't been called yet
518        """
519        if not self.figure:
520            raise EmptyFigureError
521
522        for nameiter in product(self.names, repeat=self._ndim):
523            if self[nameiter] and which in ["both", "x"]:
524                self[nameiter].xaxis.set_major_formatter(formatter)
525            if self[nameiter] and which in ["both", "y"]:
526                self[nameiter].yaxis.set_major_formatter(formatter)
527
528    def set_minor_formatter(
529        self,
530        formatter: Formatter,
531        which: str = "both",
532    ):
533        """
534        Sets the minor formatter for all of the axes.
535
536        Parameters
537        ----------
538        formatter
539            the instance of `matplotlib.ticker.Formatter` to use.
540
541        which : {'both', 'x', 'y'}
542            which axis to change (default: 'both')
543
544        Returns
545        -------
546        None
547
548        Raises
549        ------
550        EmptyFigureError
551            if `plot` hasn't been called yet
552        """
553        if not self.figure:
554            raise EmptyFigureError
555
556        for nameiter in product(self.names, repeat=self._ndim):
557            if self[nameiter] and which in ["both", "x"]:
558                self[nameiter].xaxis.set_minor_formatter(formatter)
559            if self[nameiter] and which in ["both", "y"]:
560                self[nameiter].yaxis.set_minor_formatter(formatter)

The abstract base class for plotting Fisher objects.

FisherBaseFigure( *args, options: Optional[dict] = None, hspace: float = 0.1, wspace: float = 0.1, **kwargs) 
 50    def __init__(
 51        self,
 52        *args,
 53        options: Optional[dict] = None,
 54        hspace: float = 0.1,
 55        wspace: float = 0.1,
 56        **kwargs,
 57    ):
 58        """
 59        Constructor
 60        """
 61        self._figure = None
 62        self._axes = None
 63        self._handles: MutableSequence[Artist] = []
 64        self._names = None
 65        self._labels: MutableSequence[str] = []
 66        self._options: dict = get_default_rcparams()
 67        self._ndim: int = 0
 68        self._hspace = hspace
 69        self._wspace = wspace
 70
 71        self.cycler = plt.rcParams["axes.prop_cycle"].by_key()["color"]
 72        self.current_color = iter(self.cycler)
 73
 74        if options and "style" in options:
 75            style = options.pop("style")
 76            # maybe it's one of the built-in styles
 77            if style in plt.style.available:
 78                self._options = {
 79                    **plt.style.library[style],
 80                    **get_default_rcparams(),
 81                    **options,
 82                }
 83                # we need to reset the color cycler
 84                self.cycler = (
 85                    plt.style.library[style]
 86                    .get(
 87                        "axes.prop_cycle",
 88                        plt.rcParams["axes.prop_cycle"],
 89                    )
 90                    .by_key()["color"]
 91                )
 92                self.current_color = iter(self.cycler)
 93
 94            # maybe it's a file
 95            else:
 96                # we need to reset the color cycler
 97                self.cycler = (
 98                    plt.style.core.rc_params_from_file(style)
 99                    .get(
100                        "axes.prop_cycle",
101                        plt.rcParams["axes.prop_cycle"],
102                    )
103                    .by_key()["color"]
104                )
105                self.current_color = iter(self.cycler)
106
107                self._options = {
108                    **plt.style.core.rc_params_from_file(style),
109                    **options,
110                }

Implements plotting of Fisher objects.

figure

Returns the underlying figure, an instance of matplotlib.figure.Figure.

axes

Returns the axes of the figure as a numpy array.

hspace: float

The amount of height reserved for space between subplots, expressed as a fraction of the average axis height.

wspace: float

The amount of width reserved for space between subplots, expressed as a fraction of the average axis width.

names

Returns the names of the original parameters plotted.

handles

Returns the handles of the currently drawn artists.

labels

Returns the legend labels of the currently drawn artists.

options

Returns the matplotlib options which were used for plotting.

208        self,
209        artist: Artist,
210        label: str,
211    ):
212        r"""
213        This is a convenience function for correctly updating the legend after
214        directly plotting some artist via `<instance>[<name(s)>].<method>`
215
216        Parameters
217        ----------
218        artist
219            the artist which we want to put on the legend
220
221        label : str
222            the label for the artist
223
224        Returns
225        -------
226        None
227
228        Examples
229        --------
230        Setup the plot:
231        >>> fig = FisherFigure1D()
232        >>> fig.plot(FisherMatrix(np.diag([1, 2]), names=["a", "b"]), label="Fisher matrix")
233
234        Add something to the plot that has a handle:
235        >>> handle, = fig["a"].plot([-1, 0, 1], [-1, 0, 1], color='red')
236
237        Finally, add the handle to the legend, and draw the legend:
238        >>> fig.add_artist_to_legend(handle, "linear function")
239        >>> _ = fig.legend() # the artist will now be shown correctly in the legend
240
241        Save it to a file:
242        >>> fig.savefig(
