247
248        Notes
249        -----
250        The limits of the plot are not updated automatically.
251        """
252        self.labels.append(label)
253        self.handles.append(artist)

This is a convenience function for correctly updating the legend after directly plotting some artist via <instance>[<name(s)>].<method>

Parameters
  • artist: the artist which we want to put on the legend
  • label (str): the label for the artist
Returns
  • None
Examples

Setup the plot:

>>> fig = FisherFigure1D()
>>> fig.plot(FisherMatrix(np.diag([1, 2]), names=["a", "b"]), label="Fisher matrix")

Add something to the plot that has a handle:

>>> handle, = fig["a"].plot([-1, 0, 1], [-1, 0, 1], color='red')

Finally, add the handle to the legend, and draw the legend:

>>> fig.add_artist_to_legend(handle, "linear function")
>>> _ = fig.legend() # the artist will now be shown correctly in the legend

Save it to a file:

>>> fig.savefig(
... Path(__file__).parent.parent / os.environ.get("TEMP_IMAGE_DIR") / "fisher_figure2d_add_artist_to_legend1.png",
... dpi=150)

Notes

The limits of the plot are not updated automatically.

def savefig( self, path: pathlib.Path, dpi: float = 300, bbox_inches: Union[str, matplotlib.transforms.Bbox] = 'tight', **kwargs): 
255    def savefig(
256        self,
257        path: Path,
258        dpi: float = 300,
259        bbox_inches: Union[str, Bbox] = "tight",
260        **kwargs,
261    ):
262        """
263        Convenience wrapper for `figure.savefig`.
264
265        Parameters
266        ----------
267        path : Path
268            the path where to save the figure
269
270        dpi : float, optional
271            the resolution of the saved figure (default: 300)
272
273        bbox_inches : str or Bbox, optional
274            what is the bounding box for the figure (default: 'tight')
275
276        **kwargs
277            any other keyword arguments that should be passed to
278            `figure.savefig`
279
280        Returns
281        -------
282        None
283
284        Raises
285        ------
286        EmptyFigureError
287            if `plot` hasn't been called yet
288        """
289        if not self.figure:
290            raise EmptyFigureError
291
292        self.figure.savefig(
293            path,
294            dpi=dpi,
295            bbox_inches=bbox_inches,
296            **kwargs,
297        )

Convenience wrapper for figure.savefig.

Parameters
  • path (Path): the path where to save the figure
  • dpi (float, optional): the resolution of the saved figure (default: 300)
  • bbox_inches (str or Bbox, optional): what is the bounding box for the figure (default: 'tight')
  • **kwargs: any other keyword arguments that should be passed to figure.savefig
Returns
  • None
Raises
  • EmptyFigureError: if plot hasn't been called yet

307        Parameters
308        ----------
309        which : {'both', 'x', 'y'}
310            which axis to change (default: 'both')
311
312        **kwargs
313            any keyword arguments that are also valid for
314            `matplotlib.text.Text`, see [the
315            documentation](https://matplotlib.org/stable/api/text_api.html#matplotlib.text.Text)
316            for details
317
318        Returns
319        -------
320        None
321
322        Raises
323        ------
324        EmptyFigureError
325            if `plot` hasn't been called yet
326        """
327        if not self.figure:
328            raise EmptyFigureError
329
330        for nameiter in product(self.names, repeat=self._ndim):
331            # only set the parameters which are not empty (should this be done
332            # for all of them instead?)
333            if (
334                self[nameiter]
335                and self[nameiter].get_xlabel()
336                and which in ["both", "x"]
337            ):
338                self[nameiter].set_xlabel(
339                    self[nameiter].get_xlabel(),
340                    **kwargs,
341                )
342            if (
343                self[nameiter]
344                and self[nameiter].get_ylabel()
345                and which in ["both", "y"]
346            ):
347                self[nameiter].set_ylabel(
348                    self[nameiter].get_ylabel(),
349                    **kwargs,
350                )

Collectively sets both x and y label parameters.

  • which ({'both', 'x', 'y'}): which axis to change (default: 'both')
  • **kwargs: any keyword arguments that are also valid for matplotlib.text.Text, see the documentation for details

def set_tick_params(self, which: str = 'both', **kwargs): 
352    def set_tick_params(
353        self,
354        which: str = "both",
355        **kwargs,
356    ):
357        """
358        Collectively sets both x and y tick parameters.
359
360        Parameters
361        ----------
362        which : {'both', 'x', 'y'}
363            which axis to change (default: 'both')
364
365        **kwargs
366            any keyword arguments passed to the methods for handling tick
367            parameters (such as 'fontsize', 'rotation', etc.)
368
369        Returns
370        -------
371        None
372
373        Raises
374        ------
375        EmptyFigureError
376            if `plot` hasn't been called yet
377        """
378        if not self.figure:
379            raise EmptyFigureError
380
381        for nameiter in product(self.names, repeat=self._ndim):
382            if self[nameiter] and which in ["both", "x"]:
383                for item in self[nameiter].get_xticklabels():
384                    for key, value in kwargs.items():
385                        getattr(item, f"set_{key}")(value)
386            if self[nameiter] and which in ["both", "y"]:
387                for item in self[nameiter].get_yticklabels():
388                    for key, value in kwargs.items():
389                        getattr(item, f"set_{key}")(value)
390            # also alter any exponential offsets
391            for key, value in kwargs.items():
392                if self[nameiter] and which in ["both", "x"]:
393                    getattr(
394                        self[nameiter].get_xaxis().get_offset_text(),
395                        f"set_{key}",
396                    )(value)
397                if self[nameiter] and which in ["both", "y"]:
398                    getattr(
399                        self[nameiter].get_yaxis().get_offset_text(),
400                        f"set_{key}",
401                    )(value)

Collectively sets both x and y tick parameters.

def set_major_locator(self, locator: matplotlib.ticker.Locator, which: str = 'both'): 
403    def set_major_locator(
404        self,
405        locator: Locator,
406        which: str = "both",
407    ):
408        """
409        Sets the major locator for all of the axes.
410
411        Parameters
412        ----------
413        locator
414            the instance of `matplotlib.ticker.Locator` to use.
415
416        which : {'both', 'x', 'y'}
417            which axis to change (default: 'both')
418
419        Returns
420        -------
421        None
422
423        Raises
424        ------
425        EmptyFigureError
426            if `plot` hasn't been called yet
427        """
428        if not self.figure:
429            raise EmptyFigureError
430
431        for nameiter in product(self.names, repeat=self._ndim):
432            # for some reason, we cannot reuse the same instance, so we just
433            # make a deep copy of it instead
434            if (
435                self[nameiter]
436                and np.any(self[nameiter].get_xticks())
437                and which in ["both", "x"]
438            ):
439                xloc = copy.deepcopy(locator)
440                self[nameiter].xaxis.set_major_locator(xloc)
441            if (
442                self[nameiter]
443                and np.any(self[nameiter].get_yticks())
444                and which in ["both", "y"]
445            ):
446                yloc = copy.deepcopy(locator)
447                self[nameiter].yaxis.set_major_locator(yloc)

Sets the major locator for all of the axes.

  • which ({'both', 'x', 'y'}): which axis to change (default: 'both')

class FisherFigure1D(FisherBaseFigure): 
563class FisherFigure1D(FisherBaseFigure):
564    r"""
565    Container for easy access to elements in the 1D plot.
566
567    Examples
568    --------
569    Define some Fisher matrices:
570    >>> m1 = FisherMatrix(
571    ... [[3, -2], [-2, 5]],
572    ... names=['a', 'b'],
573    ... latex_names=[r'$\mathcal{A}$', r'$\mathcal{B}$'],
574    ... )
575    >>> m2 = FisherMatrix(
576    ... [[4, 1], [1, 6]],
577    ... names=['a', 'b'],
578    ... latex_names=[r'$\mathcal{A}$', r'$\mathcal{B}$'],
579    ... )
580
581    Instantiate a figure:
582    >>> fig = FisherFigure1D()
583
584    Draw marginalized 1D plots with the previously defined Fisher matrix:
585    >>> fig.plot(m1, label='first')
586
587    Add another plot with a different color and style:
588    >>> fig.plot(m2, label='second', ls=':', color='green')
589
590    Draw some other stuff on it:
591    >>> artist, = fig.draw('a', 'plot', [-1, 0, 1], [-1, 0, 1], color='red')
592    >>> # alternatively, the below will accomplish the same thing
593    >>> # artist, = fig['a'].plot([-1, 0, 1], [-1, 0, 1], color='red')
594
595    Caveat for the above: make sure to update the legend with this artist:
596    >>> fig.add_artist_to_legend(artist, label='curve')
597
598    Add a legend:
599    >>> _ = fig.legend(ncol=3, loc='center')
600
601    Add a title:
602    >>> _ = fig.set_title('Example Fisher matrix 1D plotting')
603
604    Save it to a file:
605    >>> fig.savefig(
606    ... Path(__file__).parent.parent / os.environ.get("TEMP_IMAGE_DIR") / "fisher_figure1d_example1.png",
607    ... dpi=150)
608

610    """
611
612    def __init__(
613        self,
614        options: Optional[dict] = None,
615        max_cols: Optional[int] = None,
616        hspace: float = 0.5,
617        wspace: float = 0.1,
618    ):
619        """
620        Constructor.
621
622        Parameters
623        ----------
624        options : dict, optional
625            the dictionary containing the options for plotting. If the special
626            key 'style' is present, it attempts to use that plotting style (can
627            be one of the outputs of `matplotlib.pyplot.style.available`, or a
628            path to a file. If using a file, does not use the default rc
629            parameters).
630
631        max_cols : int, optional
632            the maximum number of columns in the final plot
633
634        hspace : float, optional
635            The amount of height reserved for space between subplots, expressed
636            as a fraction of the average axis height.
637
638        wspace : float, optional
639            The amount of width reserved for space between subplots, expressed
640            as a fraction of the average axis width.
641
642        Notes
643        -----
644        For the style sheet reference, please consult [the matplotlib
645        documentation](https://matplotlib.org/stable/gallery/style_sheets/style_sheets_reference.html).
646        """
647        super().__init__(options=options, wspace=wspace, hspace=hspace)
648        self.max_cols = max_cols
649        self._ndim = 1
650        self._hspace = hspace
651        self._wspace = wspace
652
653    def __getitem__(
654        self,
655        key: str,
656    ):
657        """
658        Returns the axis associated to the name `key`.
659        """
660        if not self.figure:
661            raise EmptyFigureError
662
663        if key not in self.names:
664            raise ParameterNotFoundError(key, self.names)
665
666        return self.axes.flat[np.where(self.names == key)][0]
667
668    def draw(
669        self,
670        name: str,
671        method: str,
672        *args,
673        **kwargs,
674    ):
675        """
676        Implements drawing of other objects on the axis.
677
678        Parameters
679        ----------
680        name : str
681            the name (label) of the parameter where we want to draw
682
683        method : str
684            the name of the method which we want to plot (such as `plot`,
685            `scatter`, etc.)
686
687        *args
688            any positional arguments passed to the method (usually some data)
689
690        **kwargs
691            any keyword arguments passed to the method (usually styling options)
692
693        Returns
694        -------
695        Artist
696            the artist that was drawn on the figure
697
698        Raises
699        ------
700        EmptyFigureError
701            if `plot` hasn't been called yet
702        """
703        if not hasattr(self[name], method):
704            raise AttributeError(
705                f"The method `{method}` is not a valid plotting method"
706            )
707
708        # get the right color
709        if "c" not in kwargs and "color" not in kwargs:
710            kwargs["color"] = next(self.current_color)
711            self.current_color = iter(self.current_color)
712
713        # hopefully the return type should be some artist, or a collection of
714        # artists
715        handles = getattr(self[name], method)(*args, **kwargs)
716        if is_iterable(handles):
717            for handle in handles:
718                if isinstance(handle, Artist) and kwargs.get("label"):
719                    self.labels.append(kwargs.get("label"))
720                    self.handles.append(handle)
721        else:
722            if isinstance(handles, Artist) and kwargs.get("label"):
723                self.labels.append(kwargs.get("label"))
724                self.handles.append(handles)
725
726        self[name].autoscale()
727        self[name].relim()
728        self[name].autoscale_view()
729
730        return handles
731
732    def plot(
733        self,
734        fisher: FisherMatrix,
735        *args,
736        **kwargs,
737    ):
738        """
739        Plots the 1D curves of the Fisher objects.
740
741        Parameters
742        ----------
743        fisher
744            the Fisher object which we want to plot
745
746        **kwargs
747            any keyword arguments used for plotting (same as `plot_curve_1d`)
748
749        Returns
750        -------
751        None
752        """
753        size = len(fisher)
754
755        added = False
756
757        # in order to preserve colors for each object, we only use the
758        # (default) cycler when the color is not explicitly set
759        if "c" not in kwargs and "color" not in kwargs:
760            kwargs["color"] = next(self.current_color)
761            self.current_color = iter(self.current_color)
762
763        if self.max_cols is not None and self.max_cols <= size:
764            full = size % self.max_cols == 0
765            layout = (
766                size // self.max_cols if full else size // self.max_cols + 1,
767                self.max_cols,
768            )
769        else:
770            layout = 1, size
771            full = True
772
773        with plt.rc_context(self.options):
774            # general figure setup
775            if self.figure:
776                fig = self.figure
777                axes = self.axes
778            else:
779                fig = plt.figure(
780                    clear=True,
781                    figsize=(2 * layout[1], 2 * layout[0]),
782                )
783                gs = fig.add_gridspec(
784                    nrows=layout[0],
785                    ncols=layout[1],
786                    hspace=self.hspace,
787                    wspace=self.wspace,
788                )
789                axes = gs.subplots()
790                if size == 1:
791                    axes = np.array([axes])
792
793            for (index, name), latex_name in zip(
794                enumerate(fisher.names),
795                fisher.latex_names,
796            ):
797                ax = axes.flat[index]
798
799                _, __, handle = plot_curve_1d(fisher, name, ax, **kwargs)
800
801                if not added and kwargs.get("label"):
802                    self.handles.append(handle)
803                    self.labels.append(kwargs["label"])
804                    added = True
805
806                _add_shading_1d(
807                    fisher.fiducials[np.where(fisher.names == name)],
808                    fisher.constraints(name, marginalized=True),
809                    ax,
810                    alpha=0.3,
811                    ec=None,
812                    **kwargs,
813                )
814
815                _add_shading_1d(
816                    fisher.fiducials[np.where(fisher.names == name)],
817                    fisher.constraints(name, marginalized=True),
818                    ax,
819                    level=2,
820                    alpha=0.1,
821                    ec=None,
822                    **kwargs,
823                )
824
825                ax.autoscale()
826                ax.set_xlabel(latex_name)
827                ax.relim()
828                ax.autoscale_view()
829
830                # the y axis should start at 0 since we're plotting a PDF
831                ax.set_ylim(0, ax.get_ylim()[-1])
832
833                ax.set_yticks([])
834
835            # remove any axes which are not drawn
836            if not full:
837                for index in range(
838                    size,
839                    layout[0] * layout[1],
840                ):
841                    # it's simpler to turn off the axis, than completely remove
842                    # it
843                    axes.flat[index].axis("off")
844
845        self._figure = fig
846        self._axes = axes
847        self._names = fisher.names
848
849    def legend(
850        self,
851        *args: Artist,
852        overwrite: bool = False,
853        loc: Union[str, tuple[float, float]] = "lower center",
854        bbox_to_anchor: Any = [0.5, 1],
855        **kwargs,
856    ):
857        """
858        Creates a legend on the figure.
859
860        Parameters
861        ----------
862        *args
863            any positional arguments for the legend
864
865        overwrite : bool, optional
866            whether to overwrite any "nice" options set by `fitk` (default:
867            False)
868
869        loc : str or tuple of floats, optional
870            which corner of the legend to use as the positioning anchor
871            (default: 'lower center')
872
873        bbox_to_anchor : Any, optional
874            the location of where to place the legend (default: `[0.5, 1]`)
875
876        **kwargs
877            any other keyword arguments for the legend
878
879        Returns
880        -------
881        Artist
882            the legend that was drawn on the figure
883
884        Raises
885        ------
886        EmptyFigureError
887            if `plot` hasn't been called yet
888        """
889        if not self.figure:
890            raise EmptyFigureError
891
892        with plt.rc_context(self.options):
893            ax = self.axes.flat[0]
894            if not overwrite:
895                if ax.get_legend():
896                    ax.get_legend().remove()
897
898                return ax.legend(
899                    self.handles,
900                    self.labels,
901                    loc=loc,
902                    bbox_to_anchor=bbox_to_anchor,
903                    bbox_transform=self.figure.transFigure,
904                    **kwargs,
905                )
906
907            return ax.legend(
908                *args,
909                loc=loc,
910                bbox_to_anchor=bbox_to_anchor,
911                **kwargs,
912            )

915        self,

929

950            raise EmptyFigureError
951

953            return self.figure.suptitle(*args, x=x, y=y, **kwargs)

Container for easy access to elements in the 1D plot.

Examples

Define some Fisher matrices:

>>> m1 = FisherMatrix(
... [[3, -2], [-2, 5]],
... names=['a', 'b'],
... latex_names=[r'$\mathcal{A}$', r'$\mathcal{B}$'],
... )
>>> m2 = FisherMatrix(
... [[4, 1], [1, 6]],
... names=['a', 'b'],
... latex_names=[r'$\mathcal{A}$', r'$\mathcal{B}$'],
... )

Instantiate a figure:

>>> fig = FisherFigure1D()

Draw marginalized 1D plots with the previously defined Fisher matrix:

>>> fig.plot(m1, label='first')

Add another plot with a different color and style:

>>> fig.plot(m2, label='second', ls=':', color='green')

Draw some other stuff on it:

>>> artist, = fig.draw('a', 'plot', [-1, 0, 1], [-1, 0, 1], color='red')
>>> # alternatively, the below will accomplish the same thing
>>> # artist, = fig['a'].plot([-1, 0, 1], [-1, 0, 1], color='red')

Caveat for the above: make sure to update the legend with this artist:

>>> fig.add_artist_to_legend(artist, label='curve')

Add a legend:

>>> _ = fig.legend(ncol=3, loc='center')

Add a title:

>>> _ = fig.set_title('Example Fisher matrix 1D plotting')

Save it to a file:

>>> fig.savefig(
... Path(__file__).parent.parent / os.environ.get("TEMP_IMAGE_DIR") / "fisher_figure1d_example1.png",
... dpi=150)

636            as a fraction of the average axis height.

646        """

649        self._ndim = 1
650        self._hspace = hspace
651        self._wspace = wspace

Constructor.

Parameters
  • options (dict, optional): the dictionary containing the options for plotting. If the special key 'style' is present, it attempts to use that plotting style (can be one of the outputs of matplotlib.pyplot.style.available, or a path to a file. If using a file, does not use the default rc parameters).
  • max_cols (int, optional): the maximum number of columns in the final plot
  • hspace (float, optional): The amount of height reserved for space between subplots, expressed as a fraction of the average axis height.
  • wspace (float, optional): The amount of width reserved for space between subplots, expressed as a fraction of the average axis width.

def draw(self, name: str, method: str, *args, **kwargs): 
668    def draw(
669        self,
670        name: str,
671        method: str,
672        *args,
673        **kwargs,
674    ):
675        """
676        Implements drawing of other objects on the axis.
677
678        Parameters
679        ----------
680        name : str
681            the name (label) of the parameter where we want to draw
682
683        method : str
684            the name of the method which we want to plot (such as `plot`,
685            `scatter`, etc.)
686
687        *args
688            any positional arguments passed to the method (usually some data)
689
690        **kwargs
691            any keyword arguments passed to the method (usually styling options)
692
693        Returns
694        -------
695        Artist
696            the artist that was drawn on the figure
697
698        Raises
699        ------
700        EmptyFigureError
701            if `plot` hasn't been called yet
702        """
703        if not hasattr(self[name], method):
704            raise AttributeError(
705                f"The method `{method}` is not a valid plotting method"
706            )
707
708        # get the right color
709        if "c" not in kwargs and "color" not in kwargs:
710            kwargs["color"] = next(self.current_color)
711            self.current_color = iter(self.current_color)
712
713        # hopefully the return type should be some artist, or a collection of
714        # artists
715        handles = getattr(self[name], method)(*args, **kwargs)
716        if is_iterable(handles):
717            for handle in handles:
718                if isinstance(handle, Artist) and kwargs.get("label"):
719                    self.labels.append(kwargs.get("label"))
720                    self.handles.append(handle)
721        else:
722            if isinstance(handles, Artist) and kwargs.get("label"):
723                self.labels.append(kwargs.get("label"))
724                self.handles.append(handles)
725
726        self[name].autoscale()
727        self[name].relim()
728        self[name].autoscale_view()
729
730        return handles

  • method (str): the name of the method which we want to plot (such as plot, scatter, etc.)

def plot(self, fisher: fitk.fisher_matrix.FisherMatrix, *args, **kwargs): 
732    def plot(
733        self,
734        fisher: FisherMatrix,
735        *args,
736        **kwargs,
737    ):
738        """
739        Plots the 1D curves of the Fisher objects.
740
741        Parameters
742        ----------
743        fisher
744            the Fisher object which we want to plot
745
746        **kwargs
747            any keyword arguments used for plotting (same as `plot_curve_1d`)
748
749        Returns
750        -------
751        None
752        """
753        size = len(fisher)
754
755        added = False
756
757        # in order to preserve colors for each object, we only use the
758        # (default) cycler when the color is not explicitly set
759        if "c" not in kwargs and "color" not in kwargs:
760            kwargs["color"] = next(self.current_color)
761            self.current_color = iter(self.current_color)
762
763        if self.max_cols is not None and self.max_cols <= size:
764            full = size % self.max_cols == 0
765            layout = (
766                size // self.max_cols if full else size // self.max_cols + 1,
767                self.max_cols,
768            )
769        else:
770            layout = 1, size
771            full = True
772
773        with plt.rc_context(self.options):
774            # general figure setup
775            if self.figure:
776                fig = self.figure
777                axes = self.axes
778            else:
779                fig = plt.figure(
780                    clear=True,
781                    figsize=(2 * layout[1], 2 * layout[0]),
782                )
783                gs = fig.add_gridspec(
784                    nrows=layout[0],
785                    ncols=layout[1],
786                    hspace=self.hspace,
787                    wspace=self.wspace,
788                )
789                axes = gs.subplots()
790                if size == 1:
791                    axes = np.array([axes])
792
793            for (index, name), latex_name in zip(
794                enumerate(fisher.names),
795                fisher.latex_names,
796            ):
797                ax = axes.flat[index]
798
799                _, __, handle = plot_curve_1d(fisher, name, ax, **kwargs)
800
801                if not added and kwargs.get("label"):
802                    self.handles.append(handle)
803                    self.labels.append(kwargs["label"])
804                    added = True
805
806                _add_shading_1d(
807                    fisher.fiducials[np.where(fisher.names == name)],
808                    fisher.constraints(name, marginalized=True),
809                    ax,
810                    alpha=0.3,
811                    ec=None,
812                    **kwargs,
813                )
814
815                _add_shading_1d(
816                    fisher.fiducials[np.where(fisher.names == name)],
817                    fisher.constraints(name, marginalized=True),
818                    ax,
819                    level=2,
820                    alpha=0.1,
821                    ec=None,
822                    **kwargs,
823                )
824
825                ax.autoscale()
826                ax.set_xlabel(latex_name)
827                ax.relim()
828                ax.autoscale_view()
829
830                # the y axis should start at 0 since we're plotting a PDF
831                ax.set_ylim(0, ax.get_ylim()[-1])
832
833                ax.set_yticks([])
834
835            # remove any axes which are not drawn
836            if not full:
837                for index in range(
838                    size,
839                    layout[0] * layout[1],
840                ):
841                    # it's simpler to turn off the axis, than completely remove
842                    # it
843                    axes.flat[index].axis("off")
844
845        self._figure = fig
846        self._axes = axes
847        self._names = fisher.names

Plots the 1D curves of the Fisher objects.

Parameters
  • fisher: the Fisher object which we want to plot
  • **kwargs: any keyword arguments used for plotting (same as plot_curve_1d)
Returns
  • None

1003    """
1004
1005    def __init__(
1006        self,
1007        options: Optional[dict] = None,
1008        hspace: float = 0,
1009        wspace: float = 0,
1010        show_1d_curves: bool = False,
1011        show_joint_dist: bool = False,
1012    ):
1013        """
1014        Constructor.
1015
1016        Parameters
1017        ----------
1018        options : dict, optional
1019            the dictionary containing the options for plotting. If the special
1020            key 'style' is present, it attempts to use that plotting style (can
1021            be one of the outputs of `matplotlib.pyplot.style.available`, or a
1022            path to a file. If using a file, does not use the default rc
1023            parameters).
1024
1025        hspace : float, optional
1026            The amount of height reserved for space between subplots, expressed
1027            as a fraction of the average axis height.
1028
1029        wspace : float, optional
1030            The amount of width reserved for space between subplots, expressed
1031            as a fraction of the average axis width.
1032
1033        show_1d_curves : bool, optional
1034            whether the 1D marginalized curves should be plotted (default:
1035            False)
1036
1037        show_joint_dist : bool, optional
1038            whether to plot the isocontours of the joint distribution (default:
1039            False)
1040
1041        Notes
1042        -----
1043        For the style sheet reference, please consult [the matplotlib
1044        documentation](https://matplotlib.org/stable/gallery/style_sheets/style_sheets_reference.html).
1045
1046        **Regarding `show_joint_dist`**: this argument specifies whether we
1047        wish to plot the p-value of the *joint* distribution, or the p-value of
1048        the probability of a single parameter lying within the bounds projected
1049        onto a parameter axis. For more details, see
1050        [arXiv:0906.0664](https://arxiv.org/abs/0906.0664), section 2.
1051        """
1052        super().__init__(options=options, wspace=wspace, hspace=hspace)
1053        self.show_1d_curves = show_1d_curves
1054        self.show_joint_dist = show_joint_dist
1055        self._ndim = 2
1056
1057    def __getitem__(
1058        self,
1059        key: tuple[str, str],
1060    ):
1061        if not self.figure:
1062            raise EmptyFigureError
1063
1064        if not isinstance(key, tuple):
1065            raise TypeError(
1066                f"Incompatible type for element access: expected `tuple`, got `{type(key)}`"
1067            )
1068
1069        name1, name2 = key
1070
1071        if name1 not in self.names:
1072            raise ParameterNotFoundError(name1, self.names)
1073        if name2 not in self.names:
1074            raise ParameterNotFoundError(name2, self.names)
1075
1076        # edge case
1077        if not self.show_1d_curves and name1 == name2:
1078            return None
1079
1080        index1 = np.where(self.names == name1)
1081        index2 = np.where(self.names == name2)
1082
1083        if index1 < index2:
1084            index1, index2 = index2, index1
1085
1086        return self.axes[index1, index2][0, 0]
1087
1088    def legend(
1089        self,
1090        *args: Artist,
1091        overwrite: bool = False,
1092        loc: Union[str, tuple[float, float]] = "upper right",
1093        bbox_to_anchor: Optional[Any] = None,
1094        **kwargs,
1095    ):
1096        """
1097        Creates a legend on the figure.
1098
1099        Parameters
1100        ----------
1101        *args
1102            any positional arguments for the legend
1103
1104        overwrite : bool, optional
1105            whether to overwrite any "nice" options set by `fitk` (default:
1106            False)
1107
1108        loc : str or tuple of floats, optional
1109            which corner of the legend to use as the positioning anchor
1110            (default: 'upper right')
1111
1112        bbox_to_anchor : Any, optional
1113            the location of where to place the legend (default: None, picked by
1114            `fitk` based on information about the plot)
1115
1116        **kwargs
1117            any other keyword arguments for the legend
1118
1119        Returns
1120        -------
1121        Artist
1122            the legend that was drawn on the figure
1123
1124        Raises
1125        ------
1126        EmptyFigureError
1127            if `plot` hasn't been called yet
1128        """
1129        if not self.figure:
1130            raise EmptyFigureError
1131
1132        with plt.rc_context(self.options):
1133            # this will always exist since we can't plot < 2 parameters
1134            ax = self[self.names[0], self.names[1]]
1135            if not overwrite:
1136                if self.show_1d_curves:
1137                    i, j = 0, -1
1138                else:
1139                    i, j = 1, -2
1140
1141                bbox_to_anchor = (
1142                    self.axes[0, j].get_position().xmax,
1143                    self.axes[i, 0].get_position().ymax,
1144                )
1145
1146                if ax.get_legend():
1147                    ax.get_legend().remove()
1148
1149                return ax.legend(
1150                    self.handles,
1151                    self.labels,
1152                    loc=loc,
1153                    bbox_to_anchor=bbox_to_anchor,
1154                    bbox_transform=self.figure.transFigure,
1155                    **kwargs,
1156                )
1157
1158            return ax.legend(
1159                *args,
1160                loc=loc,
1161                bbox_to_anchor=bbox_to_anchor,
1162                **kwargs,
1163            )
1164
1165    def set_title(
1166        self,
1167        *args,
1168        overwrite: bool = False,
1169        xscale: float = 0.5,
1170        yscale: float = 1.08,
1171        **kwargs,
1172    ):
1173        """
1174        Thin wrapper for setting the title of the figure with the correct
1175        options.
1176
1177        Parameters
1178        ----------
1179        *args
1180            any positional arguments to `figure.suptitle`
1181
1182        xscale : float, optional
1183            the x position of the title (default: `0.5`)
1184
1185        yscale : float, optional
1186            the y position of the title (default: `1.08`)
1187
1188        **kwargs
1189            any keyword arguments to `figure.suptitle`
1190
1191        Returns
1192        -------
1193        Artist
1194            the title that was drawn on the figure
1195
1196        Raises
1197        ------
1198        EmptyFigureError
1199            if `plot` hasn't been called yet
1200        """
1201        if not self.figure:
1202            raise EmptyFigureError
1203
1204        with plt.rc_context(self.options):
1205            if not overwrite:
1206                if self.show_1d_curves:
1207                    i, j = 0, -1
1208                else:
1209                    i, j = 1, -2
1210
1211                x, y = (
1212                    self.axes[0, j].get_position().xmax,
1213                    self.axes[i, 0].get_position().ymax,
1214                )
1215
1216                return self.figure.suptitle(
1217                    *args,
1218                    x=x * xscale,
1219                    y=y * yscale,
1220                    **kwargs,
1221                )
1222
1223            return self.figure.suptitle(*args, **kwargs)
1224
1225    def draw(
1226        self,
1227        name1: str,
1228        name2: str,
1229        method: str,
1230        *args,
1231        **kwargs,
1232    ):
1233        """
1234        Implements drawing of other objects on the axis.
1235
1236        Parameters
1237        ----------
1238        name1 : str
1239            the name (label) of the first parameter where we want to draw
1240
1241        name2 : str
1242            the name (label) of the second parameter where we want to draw
1243
1244        method : str
1245            the name of the method which we want to plot (such as `plot`,
1246            `scatter`, etc.)
1247
1248        *args
1249            any positional arguments passed to the method (usually some data)
1250
1251        **kwargs
1252            any keyword arguments passed to the method (usually styling options)
1253
1254        Returns
1255        -------
1256        Artist
1257            the artist that was drawn on the figure
1258
1259        Raises
1260        ------
1261        EmptyFigureError
1262            if `plot` hasn't been called yet
1263        """
1264        if not hasattr(self[name1, name2], method):
1265            raise AttributeError(
1266                f"The method `{method}` is not a valid plotting method"
1267            )
1268
1269        # get the right color
1270        if "c" not in kwargs and "color" not in kwargs:
1271            kwargs["color"] = next(self.current_color)
1272            self.current_color = iter(self.current_color)
1273
1274        with plt.rc_context(self.options):
1275            # hopefully the return type should be some artist, or a collection
1276            # of artists
1277            handles = getattr(self[name1, name2], method)(*args, **kwargs)
1278            if is_iterable(handles):
1279                for handle in handles:
1280                    if isinstance(handle, Artist) and kwargs.get("label"):
1281                        self.labels.append(kwargs["label"])
1282                        self.handles.append(handle)
1283            else:
1284                if isinstance(handles, Artist) and kwargs.get("label"):
1285                    self.labels.append(kwargs["label"])
1286                    self.handles.append(handles)
1287
1288        self[name1, name2].autoscale()
1289        self[name1, name2].relim()
1290        self[name1, name2].autoscale_view()
1291
1292        return handles
1293
1294    def plot(
1295        self,
1296        fisher: FisherMatrix,
1297        *args,
1298        **kwargs,
1299    ):
1300        r"""
1301        Plots the 2D contours (and optionally 1D curves) of the Fisher objects.
1302
1303        Parameters
1304        ----------
1305        fisher : FisherMatrix
1306            the Fisher object which we want to plot
1307
1308        **kwargs
1309            any keyword arguments used for plotting (same as `plot_curve_2d`)
1310
1311        Returns
1312        -------
1313        None
1314
1315        Examples
1316        --------
1317        Define a Fisher matrix:
1318        >>> m = FisherMatrix([[3, -2], [-2, 5]], names=['a', 'b'], latex_names=[r'$\mathcal{A}$', r'$\mathcal{B}$'])
1319
1320        Initiate a figure:
1321        >>> fig = FisherFigure2D(show_1d_curves=True)
1322
1323        Draw a "triangle plot" with the previously defined Fisher matrix:
1324        >>> fig.plot(m)
1325
1326        Save it to a file:
1327        >>> fig.savefig(
1328        ... Path(__file__).parent.parent / os.environ.get("TEMP_IMAGE_DIR") / "fisher_figure2d_plot_example.png",
1329        ... dpi=150)

1332        """
1333        size = len(fisher)
1334
1335        if size < 2:
1336            raise ValueError("Unable to make a 2D plot with < 2 parameters")
1337
1338        if self.names is not None:
1339            # make sure they have the same names; if not, raise an error
1340            if set(self.names) != set(fisher.names):
1341                raise ValueError(
1342                    f"The Fisher object names ({fisher.names}) "
1343                    f"do not match those on the figure ({self.names})"
1344                )
1345
1346            # otherwise, we reshuffle them
1347            fisher = fisher.sort(key=self.names)
1348
1349        # in order to preserve colors for each object, we only use the
1350        # (default) cycler when the color is not explicitly set
1351        if "c" not in kwargs and "color" not in kwargs:
1352            kwargs["color"] = next(self.current_color)
1353            self.current_color = iter(self.current_color)
1354
1355        with plt.rc_context(self.options):
1356            # general figure setup
1357            if self.figure:
1358                fig = self.figure
1359                ax = self.axes
1360            else:
1361                fig = plt.figure(
1362                    figsize=(2 * size, 2 * size),
1363                    clear=True,
1364                )
1365                ax = fig.add_gridspec(
1366                    nrows=size,
1367                    ncols=size,
1368                    hspace=self.hspace,
1369                    wspace=self.wspace,
1370                ).subplots(
1371                    sharex="col",
1372                    sharey=False,
1373                )
1374
1375            # set automatic limits
1376            for i, j in product(range(size), repeat=2):
1377                if i == j:
1378                    ax[i, i].set_yticks([])
1379                    ax[i, i].set_yticklabels([])
1380                    if i < size - 1:
1381                        ax[i, i].get_xaxis().set_visible(False)
1382                if i > 0 and 0 < j < size - 1:
1383                    ax[i, j].set_yticks([])
1384                    ax[i, j].set_yticklabels([])
1385                if i > j and i != size - 1:
1386                    ax[i, j].get_xaxis().set_visible(False)
1387
1388            # flag for whether the current artist has already been added to the
1389            # legend handle
1390            added = False
1391            # loop over the parameters
1392            for i, j in product(range(len(fisher.names)), repeat=2):
1393                namey, latex_namey, namex, latex_namex = (
1394                    fisher.names[i],
1395                    fisher.latex_names[i],
1396                    fisher.names[j],
1397                    fisher.latex_names[j],
1398                )
1399                # labels for 2D contours (increasing y)
1400                if i > 0 and j == 0:
1401                    ax[i, j].set_ylabel(latex_namey)
1402
1403                # labels for 2D contours (increasing x)
1404                if i == size - 1:
1405                    ax[i, j].set_xlabel(latex_namex)
1406
1407                # removing any unnecessary axes from the gridspec
1408                if i < j and self.figure is None:
1409                    # calling `remove()` is better than `axis("off")` because
1410                    # then we obtain the proper bounding box
1411                    ax[i, j].remove()
1412
1413                # plotting the 2D contours
1414                elif i > j:
1415                    # plot 1-sigma 2D curves
1416                    # NOTE this is the "68% of the probability of a
1417                    # single parameter lying within the bounds projected
1418                    # onto a parameter axis"
1419                    _, __, handle = plot_curve_2d(
1420                        fisher,
1421                        namex,
1422                        namey,
1423                        ax=ax[i, j],
1424                        scaling_factor=1
1425                        if not self.show_joint_dist
1426                        else np.sqrt(_get_chisq(1)),
1427                        fill=False,
1428                        zorder=20,
1429                        **kwargs,
1430                    )
1431
1432                    if not added and kwargs.get("label"):
1433                        self.handles.append(handle)
1434                        self.labels.append(kwargs["label"])
1435                        added = True
1436
1437                    # same thing, but shaded
1438                    plot_curve_2d(
1439                        fisher,
1440                        namex,
1441                        namey,
1442                        ax=ax[i, j],
1443                        scaling_factor=1
1444                        if not self.show_joint_dist
1445                        else np.sqrt(_get_chisq(1)),
1446                        fill=True,
1447                        alpha=0.2,
1448                        ec=None,
1449                        zorder=20,
1450                        **kwargs,
1451                    )
1452
1453                    # the 2-sigma
1454                    plot_curve_2d(
1455                        fisher,
1456                        namex,
1457                        namey,
1458                        ax=ax[i, j],
1459                        scaling_factor=2
1460                        if not self.show_joint_dist
1461                        else np.sqrt(_get_chisq(2)),
1462                        fill=False,
1463                        zorder=20,
1464                        **kwargs,
1465                    )
1466                    # same thing, but shaded
1467                    plot_curve_2d(
1468                        fisher,
1469                        namex,
1470                        namey,
1471                        ax=ax[i, j],
1472                        scaling_factor=2
1473                        if not self.show_joint_dist
1474                        else np.sqrt(_get_chisq(2)),
1475                        fill=True,
1476                        alpha=0.1,
1477                        ec=None,
1478                        zorder=20,
1479                        **kwargs,
1480                    )
1481
1482                if i == j:
1483                    # plotting the 1D Gaussians
1484                    if self.show_1d_curves is True:
1485                        plot_curve_1d(
1486                            fisher,
1487                            namex,
1488                            ax=ax[i, i],
1489                            **kwargs,
1490                        )
1491
1492                    else:
1493                        if self.figure is None:
1494                            ax[i, i].remove()
1495
1496            # set automatic limits
1497            for i, j in product(range(size), repeat=2):
1498                try:
1499                    ax[i, j].relim()
1500                    ax[i, j].autoscale_view()
1501                    if i == j:
1502                        ax[i, i].autoscale()
1503                        ax[i, i].set_ylim(0, ax[i, i].get_ylim()[-1])
1504                        ax[i, i].set_yticks([])
1505                        ax[i, i].set_yticklabels([])
1506                except AttributeError:
1507                    pass
1508
1509        self._figure = fig
1510        self._axes = ax
1511        self._names = fisher.names

Container for easy access to elements in the 2D plot.

Examples

Define some Fisher matrices:

>>> m1 = FisherMatrix(
... [[3, -2], [-2, 5]],
... names=['a', 'b'],
... latex_names=[r'$\mathcal{A}$', r'$\mathcal{B}$'],
... )
>>> m2 = FisherMatrix(
... [[4, 1], [1, 6]],
... names=['a', 'b'],
... latex_names=[r'$\mathcal{A}$', r'$\mathcal{B}$'],
... )

Instantiate a figure:

>>> fig = FisherFigure2D(show_1d_curves=True)

Draw a "triangle plot" with the previously defined Fisher matrix:

>>> fig.plot(m1, label='first')

Add a plot with a different color and style:

>>> fig.plot(m2, label='second', ls=':', color='green')

Draw some other stuff on it:

>>> artist, = fig.draw('a', 'b', 'plot', [-1, 0, 1], [-1, 0, 1], color='red')
>>> # alternatively, the below will accomplish the same thing
>>> # artist, = fig['a', 'b'].plot([-1, 0, 1], [-1, 0, 1], color='red')

Caveat: make sure to update the legend with this artist:

>>> fig.add_artist_to_legend(artist, label='curve')

Add a legend:

>>> _ = fig.legend()

Add a title:

>>> _ = fig.set_title('Example Fisher matrix 2D plotting')

Save it to a file:

>>> fig.savefig(
... Path(__file__).parent.parent / os.environ.get("TEMP_IMAGE_DIR") / "fisher_figure2d_example1.png",
... dpi=150)

1020            key 'style' is present, it attempts to use that plotting style (can

1023            parameters).
1024
1025        hspace : float, optional
1026            The amount of height reserved for space between subplots, expressed
1027            as a fraction of the average axis height.
1028
1029        wspace : float, optional

1035            False)

1045
1046        **Regarding `show_joint_dist`**: this argument specifies whether we
1047        wish to plot the p-value of the *joint* distribution, or the p-value of
1048        the probability of a single parameter lying within the bounds projected
1049        onto a parameter axis. For more details, see
1050        [arXiv:0906.0664](https://arxiv.org/abs/0906.0664), section 2.
1051        """

Constructor.

Parameters
  • options (dict, optional): the dictionary containing the options for plotting. If the special key 'style' is present, it attempts to use that plotting style (can be one of the outputs of matplotlib.pyplot.style.available, or a path to a file. If using a file, does not use the default rc parameters).
  • hspace (float, optional): The amount of height reserved for space between subplots, expressed as a fraction of the average axis height.
  • wspace (float, optional): The amount of width reserved for space between subplots, expressed as a fraction of the average axis width.
  • show_1d_curves (bool, optional): whether the 1D marginalized curves should be plotted (default: False)
  • show_joint_dist (bool, optional): whether to plot the isocontours of the joint distribution (default: False)
Notes

For the style sheet reference, please consult the matplotlib documentation.

Regarding show_joint_dist: this argument specifies whether we wish to plot the p-value of the joint distribution, or the p-value of the probability of a single parameter lying within the bounds projected onto a parameter axis. For more details, see arXiv:0906.0664, section 2.

def legend( self, *args: matplotlib.artist.Artist, overwrite: bool = False, loc: Union[str, tuple[float, float]] = 'upper right', bbox_to_anchor: Optional[Any] = None, **kwargs): 
1088    def legend(
1089        self,
1090        *args: Artist,
1091        overwrite: bool = False,
1092        loc: Union[str, tuple[float, float]] = "upper right",
1093        bbox_to_anchor: Optional[Any] = None,
1094        **kwargs,
1095    ):
1096        """
1097        Creates a legend on the figure.
1098
1099        Parameters
1100        ----------
1101        *args
1102            any positional arguments for the legend
1103
1104        overwrite : bool, optional
1105            whether to overwrite any "nice" options set by `fitk` (default:
1106            False)
1107
1108        loc : str or tuple of floats, optional
1109            which corner of the legend to use as the positioning anchor
1110            (default: 'upper right')
1111
1112        bbox_to_anchor : Any, optional
1113            the location of where to place the legend (default: None, picked by
1114            `fitk` based on information about the plot)
1115
1116        **kwargs
1117            any other keyword arguments for the legend
1118
1119        Returns
1120        -------
1121        Artist
1122            the legend that was drawn on the figure
1123
1124        Raises
1125        ------
1126        EmptyFigureError
1127            if `plot` hasn't been called yet
1128        """
1129        if not self.figure:
1130            raise EmptyFigureError
1131
1132        with plt.rc_context(self.options):
1133            # this will always exist since we can't plot < 2 parameters
1134            ax = self[self.names[0], self.names[1]]
1135            if not overwrite:
1136                if self.show_1d_curves:
1137                    i, j = 0, -1
1138                else:
1139                    i, j = 1, -2
1140
1141                bbox_to_anchor = (
1142                    self.axes[0, j].get_position().xmax,
1143                    self.axes[i, 0].get_position().ymax,
1144                )
1145
1146                if ax.get_legend():
1147                    ax.get_legend().remove()
1148
1149                return ax.legend(
1150                    self.handles,
1151                    self.labels,
1152                    loc=loc,
1153                    bbox_to_anchor=bbox_to_anchor,
1154                    bbox_transform=self.figure.transFigure,
1155                    **kwargs,
1156                )
1157
1158            return ax.legend(
1159                *args,
1160                loc=loc,
1161                bbox_to_anchor=bbox_to_anchor,
1162                **kwargs,
1163            )

def draw(self, name1: str, name2: str, method: str, *args, **kwargs): 
1225    def draw(
1226        self,
1227        name1: str,
1228        name2: str,
1229        method: str,
1230        *args,
1231        **kwargs,
1232    ):
1233        """
1234        Implements drawing of other objects on the axis.
1235
1236        Parameters
1237        ----------
1238        name1 : str
1239            the name (label) of the first parameter where we want to draw
1240
1241        name2 : str
1242            the name (label) of the second parameter where we want to draw
1243
1244        method : str
1245            the name of the method which we want to plot (such as `plot`,
1246            `scatter`, etc.)
1247
1248        *args
1249            any positional arguments passed to the method (usually some data)
1250
1251        **kwargs
1252            any keyword arguments passed to the method (usually styling options)
1253
1254        Returns
1255        -------
1256        Artist
1257            the artist that was drawn on the figure
1258
1259        Raises
1260        ------
1261        EmptyFigureError
1262            if `plot` hasn't been called yet
1263        """
1264        if not hasattr(self[name1, name2], method):
1265            raise AttributeError(
1266                f"The method `{method}` is not a valid plotting method"
1267            )
1268
1269        # get the right color
1270        if "c" not in kwargs and "color" not in kwargs:
1271            kwargs["color"] = next(self.current_color)
1272            self.current_color = iter(self.current_color)
1273
1274        with plt.rc_context(self.options):
1275            # hopefully the return type should be some artist, or a collection
1276            # of artists
1277            handles = getattr(self[name1, name2], method)(*args, **kwargs)
1278            if is_iterable(handles):
1279                for handle in handles:
1280                    if isinstance(handle, Artist) and kwargs.get("label"):
1281                        self.labels.append(kwargs["label"])
1282                        self.handles.append(handle)
1283            else:
1284                if isinstance(handles, Artist) and kwargs.get("label"):
1285                    self.labels.append(kwargs["label"])
1286                    self.handles.append(handles)
1287
1288        self[name1, name2].autoscale()
1289        self[name1, name2].relim()
1290        self[name1, name2].autoscale_view()
1291
1292        return handles

Implements drawing of other objects on the axis.

  • name2 (str): the name (label) of the second parameter where we want to draw
  • method (str): the name of the method which we want to plot (such as plot, scatter, etc.)

1332        """
1333        size = len(fisher)
1334
1335        if size < 2:
1336            raise ValueError("Unable to make a 2D plot with < 2 parameters")
1337
1338        if self.names is not None:
1339            # make sure they have the same names; if not, raise an error
1340            if set(self.names) != set(fisher.names):
1341                raise ValueError(
1342                    f"The Fisher object names ({fisher.names}) "
1343                    f"do not match those on the figure ({self.names})"
1344                )
1345
1346            # otherwise, we reshuffle them
1347            fisher = fisher.sort(key=self.names)
1348
1349        # in order to preserve colors for each object, we only use the
1350        # (default) cycler when the color is not explicitly set
1351        if "c" not in kwargs and "color" not in kwargs:
1352            kwargs["color"] = next(self.current_color)
1353            self.current_color = iter(self.current_color)
1354
1355        with plt.rc_context(self.options):
1356            # general figure setup
1357            if self.figure:
1358                fig = self.figure
1359                ax = self.axes
1360            else:
1361                fig = plt.figure(
1362                    figsize=(2 * size, 2 * size),
1363                    clear=True,
1364                )
1365                ax = fig.add_gridspec(
1366                    nrows=size,
1367                    ncols=size,
1368                    hspace=self.hspace,
1369                    wspace=self.wspace,
1370                ).subplots(
1371                    sharex="col",
1372                    sharey=False,
1373                )
1374
1375            # set automatic limits
1376            for i, j in product(range(size), repeat=2):
1377                if i == j:
1378                    ax[i, i].set_yticks([])
1379                    ax[i, i].set_yticklabels([])
1380                    if i < size - 1:
1381                        ax[i, i].get_xaxis().set_visible(False)
1382                if i > 0 and 0 < j < size - 1:
1383                    ax[i, j].set_yticks([])
1384                    ax[i, j].set_yticklabels([])
1385                if i > j and i != size - 1:
1386                    ax[i, j].get_xaxis().set_visible(False)
1387
1388            # flag for whether the current artist has already been added to the
1389            # legend handle
1390            added = False
1391            # loop over the parameters
1392            for i, j in product(range(len(fisher.names)), repeat=2):
1393                namey, latex_namey, namex, latex_namex = (
1394                    fisher.names[i],
1395                    fisher.latex_names[i],
1396                    fisher.names[j],
1397                    fisher.latex_names[j],
1398                )
1399                # labels for 2D contours (increasing y)
1400                if i > 0 and j == 0:
1401                    ax[i, j].set_ylabel(latex_namey)
1402
1403                # labels for 2D contours (increasing x)
1404                if i == size - 1:
1405                    ax[i, j].set_xlabel(latex_namex)
1406
1407                # removing any unnecessary axes from the gridspec
1408                if i < j and self.figure is None:
1409                    # calling `remove()` is better than `axis("off")` because
1410                    # then we obtain the proper bounding box
1411                    ax[i, j].remove()
1412
1413                # plotting the 2D contours
1414                elif i > j:
1415                    # plot 1-sigma 2D curves
1416                    # NOTE this is the "68% of the probability of a
1417                    # single parameter lying within the bounds projected
1418                    # onto a parameter axis"
1419                    _, __, handle = plot_curve_2d(
1420                        fisher,
1421                        namex,
1422                        namey,
1423                        ax=ax[i, j],
1424                        scaling_factor=1
1425                        if not self.show_joint_dist
1426                        else np.sqrt(_get_chisq(1)),
1427                        fill=False,
1428                        zorder=20,
1429                        **kwargs,
1430                    )
1431
1432                    if not added and kwargs.get("label"):
1433                        self.handles.append(handle)
1434                        self.labels.append(kwargs["label"])
1435                        added = True
1436
1437                    # same thing, but shaded
1438                    plot_curve_2d(
1439                        fisher,
1440                        namex,
1441                        namey,
1442                        ax=ax[i, j],
1443                        scaling_factor=1
1444                        if not self.show_joint_dist
1445                        else np.sqrt(_get_chisq(1)),
1446                        fill=True,
1447                        alpha=0.2,
1448                        ec=None,
1449                        zorder=20,
1450                        **kwargs,
1451                    )
1452
1453                    # the 2-sigma
1454                    plot_curve_2d(
1455                        fisher,
1456                        namex,
1457                        namey,
1458                        ax=ax[i, j],
1459                        scaling_factor=2
1460                        if not self.show_joint_dist
1461                        else np.sqrt(_get_chisq(2)),
1462                        fill=False,
1463                        zorder=20,
1464                        **kwargs,
1465                    )
1466                    # same thing, but shaded
1467                    plot_curve_2d(
1468                        fisher,
1469                        namex,
1470                        namey,
1471                        ax=ax[i, j],
1472                        scaling_factor=2
1473                        if not self.show_joint_dist
1474                        else np.sqrt(_get_chisq(2)),
1475                        fill=True,
1476                        alpha=0.1,
1477                        ec=None,
1478                        zorder=20,
1479                        **kwargs,
1480                    )
1481
1482                if i == j:
1483                    # plotting the 1D Gaussians
1484                    if self.show_1d_curves is True:
1485                        plot_curve_1d(
1486                            fisher,
1487                            namex,
1488                            ax=ax[i, i],
1489                            **kwargs,
1490                        )
1491
1492                    else:
1493                        if self.figure is None:
1494                            ax[i, i].remove()
1495
1496            # set automatic limits
1497            for i, j in product(range(size), repeat=2):
1498                try:
1499                    ax[i, j].relim()
1500                    ax[i, j].autoscale_view()
1501                    if i == j:
1502                        ax[i, i].autoscale()
1503                        ax[i, i].set_ylim(0, ax[i, i].get_ylim()[-1])
1504                        ax[i, i].set_yticks([])
1505                        ax[i, i].set_yticklabels([])
1506                except AttributeError:
1507                    pass
1508
1509        self._figure = fig
1510        self._axes = ax
1511        self._names = fisher.names

Plots the 2D contours (and optionally 1D curves) of the Fisher objects.

Parameters
  • fisher (FisherMatrix): the Fisher object which we want to plot
  • **kwargs: any keyword arguments used for plotting (same as plot_curve_2d)
Returns
  • None
Examples

Define a Fisher matrix:

>>> m = FisherMatrix([[3, -2], [-2, 5]], names=['a', 'b'], latex_names=[r'$\mathcal{A}$', r'$\mathcal{B}$'])

Initiate a figure:

>>> fig = FisherFigure2D(show_1d_curves=True)

Draw a "triangle plot" with the previously defined Fisher matrix:

>>> fig.plot(m)

Save it to a file:

>>> fig.savefig(
... Path(__file__).parent.parent / os.environ.get("TEMP_IMAGE_DIR") / "fisher_figure2d_plot_example.png",
... dpi=150)

1632    ... [[3, -2], [-2, 5]],
1633    ... names=['a', 'b'],
1634    ... latex_names=[r'$\mathcal{A}$', r'$\mathcal{B}$'],
1635    ... )
1636
1637    Draw the marginalized parameter `a`:
1638    >>> fig, ax, artist = plot_curve_1d(m, name='a', ls='--', color='red')
1639
1640    Save it to a file:
1641    >>> fig.savefig(
1642    ... Path(__file__).parent.parent / os.environ.get("TEMP_IMAGE_DIR") / "plot_curve_1d_example1.png",
1643    ... dpi=100)

1647    if ax is None:
1648        _, ax = plt.subplots()
1649
1650    fid = fisher.fiducials[np.where(fisher.names == name)]
1651    sigma = fisher.constraints(name, marginalized=True)
1652
1653    return _add_plot_1d(fid, sigma, ax=ax, **kwargs)

Plots a 1D curve (usually marginalized Gaussian) from a Fisher object.

Parameters
  • fisher (FisherMatrix): the Fisher matrix which we want to plot
  • name (str): the name of the parameter which we want to plot
  • ax (matplotlib.axes.Axes, optional): the axis on which we want to plot the contour (default: None). If None, plots to a new figure.
  • **kwargs: any keyword arguments passed to matplotlib.pyplot.plot
Returns
  • A 3-tuple (Figure, Axes, Artist): The figure and the axis on which the artist was drawn on, as well as the artist itself.
Examples

Define a Fisher matrix:

>>> m = FisherMatrix(
... [[3, -2], [-2, 5]],
... names=['a', 'b'],
... latex_names=[r'$\mathcal{A}$', r'$\mathcal{B}$'],
... )

Draw the marginalized parameter a:

>>> fig, ax, artist = plot_curve_1d(m, name='a', ls='--', color='red')

Save it to a file:

>>> fig.savefig(
... Path(__file__).parent.parent / os.environ.get("TEMP_IMAGE_DIR") / "plot_curve_1d_example1.png",
... dpi=100)

1699    ... )
1700
1701    Draw the 1$\sigma$ contour of the parameter combination `a`, `b`:
1702    >>> fig, ax, artist = plot_curve_2d(m, name1='a', name2='b', ls='--', color='red', fill=False)
1703
1704    Rescale the view a bit:
1705    >>> _ = ax.autoscale()
1706    >>> _ = ax.relim()
1707    >>> _ = ax.autoscale_view()
1708
1709    Save it to a file:
1710    >>> fig.savefig(
1711    ... Path(__file__).parent.parent / os.environ.get("TEMP_IMAGE_DIR") / "plot_curve_2d_example1.png",
1712    ... dpi=100)

1718    The limits of the plot are not updated automatically.
1719    """
1720    if ax is None:
1721        _, ax = plt.subplots()
1722
1723    fidx = fisher.fiducials[np.where(fisher.names == name1)]
1724    fidy = fisher.fiducials[np.where(fisher.names == name2)]
1725
1726    a, b, angle = _get_ellipse(fisher, name1, name2)
1727
1728    patch = ax.add_patch(
1729        Ellipse(
1730            xy=(fidx, fidy),
1731            width=2 * a * scaling_factor,
1732            height=2 * b * scaling_factor,
1733            angle=angle,
1734            **kwargs,
1735        ),
1736    )
1737
1738    return (ax.get_figure(), ax, patch)

Plots a 2D curve (usually ellipse) from two parameters of a Fisher object.

Parameters
  • fisher (FisherMatrix): the Fisher matrix which we want to plot
  • name1 (str): the name of the first parameter which we want to plot
  • name2 (str): the name of the second parameter which we want to plot
  • ax (matplotlib.axes.Axes, optional): the axis on which we want to plot the contour (default: None). If None, plots to a new figure.
  • **kwargs: any keyword arguments passed to matplotlib.patches.Ellipse
Returns
  • A 3-tuple (Figure, Axes, Artist): The figure and the axis on which the artist was drawn on, as well as the artist itself.
Examples

Define a Fisher matrix:

>>> m = FisherMatrix(
... [[3, -2], [-2, 5]],
... names=['a', 'b'],
... fiducials=[1, -2],
... latex_names=[r'$\mathcal{A}$', r'$\mathcal{B}$'],
... )

Draw the 1$\sigma$ contour of the parameter combination a, b:

>>> fig, ax, artist = plot_curve_2d(m, name1='a', name2='b', ls='--', color='red', fill=False)

Rescale the view a bit:

>>> _ = ax.autoscale()
>>> _ = ax.relim()
>>> _ = ax.autoscale_view()

Save it to a file:

>>> fig.savefig(
... Path(__file__).parent.parent / os.environ.get("TEMP_IMAGE_DIR") / "plot_curve_2d_example1.png",
... dpi=100)

Notes

The limits of the plot are not updated automatically.
